2226  if (match(V, m_Exact(m_LShr(m_Value(), m_Value()))) ||
2227  match(V, m_Exact(m_UDiv(m_Value(), m_Value())))) {
2228  return isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(cast<Operator>(V)->getOperand(0), OrZero,
2229  Depth, Q);
2230  }
2231 
2232  return false;
2233 }
2234 
2235 /// Test whether a GEP's result is known to be non-null.
2236 ///
2237 /// Uses properties inherent in a GEP to try to determine whether it is known
2238 /// to be non-null.
2239 ///
2240 /// Currently this routine does not support vector GEPs.
2241 static bool isGEPKnownNonNull(const GEPOperator *GEP, unsigned Depth,
2242  const Query &Q) {
2243  const Function *F = nullptr;
2244  if (const Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(GEP))
2245  F = I->getFunction();
2246 
2247  if (!GEP->isInBounds() ||
2248  NullPointerIsDefined(F, GEP->getPointerAddressSpace()))
2249  return false;
2250 
2251  // FIXME: Support vector-GEPs.
2252  assert(GEP->getType()->isPointerTy() && "We only support plain pointer GEP");
2253 
2254  // If the base pointer is non-null, we cannot walk to a null address with an
2255  // inbounds GEP in address space zero.
2256  if (isKnownNonZero(GEP->getPointerOperand(), Depth, Q))
2257  return true;
2258 
2259  // Walk the GEP operands and see if any operand introduces a non-zero offset.
2260  // If so, then the GEP cannot produce a null pointer, as doing so would
2261  // inherently violate the inbounds contract within address space zero.
2262  for (gep_type_iterator GTI = gep_type_begin(GEP), GTE = gep_type_end(GEP);
2263  GTI != GTE; ++GTI) {
2264  // Struct types are easy -- they must always be indexed by a constant.
2265  if (StructType *STy = GTI.getStructTypeOrNull()) {
2266  ConstantInt *OpC = cast<ConstantInt>(GTI.getOperand());
2267  unsigned ElementIdx = OpC->getZExtValue();
2268  const StructLayout *SL = Q.DL.getStructLayout(STy);
2269  uint64_t ElementOffset = SL->getElementOffset(ElementIdx);
2270  if (ElementOffset > 0)
2271  return true;
2272  continue;
2273  }
2274 
2275  // If we have a zero-sized type, the index doesn't matter. Keep looping.
2276  if (Q.DL.getTypeAllocSize(GTI.getIndexedType()).isZero())
2277  continue;
2278 
2279  // Fast path the constant operand case both for efficiency and so we don't
2280  // increment Depth when just zipping down an all-constant GEP.
2281  if (ConstantInt *OpC = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(GTI.getOperand())) {
2282  if (!OpC->isZero())
2283  return true;
2284  continue;
2285  }
2286 
2287  // We post-increment Depth here because while isKnownNonZero increments it
2288  // as well, when we pop back up that increment won't persist. We don't want
2289  // to recurse 10k times just because we have 10k GEP operands. We don't
2290  // bail completely out because we want to handle constant GEPs regardless
2291  // of depth.
2292  if (Depth++ >= MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
2293  continue;
2294 
2295  if (isKnownNonZero(GTI.getOperand(), Depth, Q))
2296  return true;
2297  }
2298 
2299  return false;
2300 }
2301 
2302 static bool isKnownNonNullFromDominatingCondition(const Value *V,
2303  const Instruction *CtxI,
2304  const DominatorTree *DT) {
2305  assert(!isa<Constant>(V) && "Called for constant?");
2306 
2307  if (!CtxI || !DT)
2308  return false;
2309 
2310  unsigned NumUsesExplored = 0;
2311  for (const auto *U : V->users()) {
2312  // Avoid massive lists
2313  if (NumUsesExplored >= DomConditionsMaxUses)
2314  break;
2315  NumUsesExplored++;
2316 
2317  // If the value is used as an argument to a call or invoke, then argument
2318  // attributes may provide an answer about null-ness.
2319  if (const auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(U))
2320  if (auto *CalledFunc = CB->getCalledFunction())
2321  for (const Argument &Arg : CalledFunc->args())
2322  if (CB->getArgOperand(Arg.getArgNo()) == V &&
2323  Arg.hasNonNullAttr(/* AllowUndefOrPoison */ false) &&
2324  DT->dominates(CB, CtxI))
2325  return true;
2326 
2327  // If the value is used as a load/store, then the pointer must be non null.
2328  if (V == getLoadStorePointerOperand(U)) {
2329  const Instruction *I = cast<Instruction>(U);
2330  if (!NullPointerIsDefined(I->getFunction(),
2331  V->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace()) &&
2332  DT->dominates(I, CtxI))
2333  return true;
2334  }
2335 
2336  // Consider only compare instructions uniquely controlling a branch
2337  Value *RHS;
2338  CmpInst::Predicate Pred;
2339  if (!match(U, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Specific(V), m_Value(RHS))))
2340  continue;
2341 
2342  bool NonNullIfTrue;
2343  if (cmpExcludesZero(Pred, RHS))
2344  NonNullIfTrue = true;
2345  else if (cmpExcludesZero(CmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred), RHS))
2346  NonNullIfTrue = false;
2347  else
2348  continue;
2349 
2350  SmallVector<const User *, 4> WorkList;
2351  SmallPtrSet<const User *, 4> Visited;
2352  for (const auto *CmpU : U->users()) {
2353  assert(WorkList.empty() && "Should be!");
2354  if (Visited.insert(CmpU).second)
2355  WorkList.push_back(CmpU);
2356 
2357  while (!WorkList.empty()) {
2358  auto *Curr = WorkList.pop_back_val();
2359 
2360  // If a user is an AND, add all its users to the work list. We only
2361  // propagate "pred != null" condition through AND because it is only
2362  // correct to assume that all conditions of AND are met in true branch.
2363  // TODO: Support similar logic of OR and EQ predicate?
2364  if (NonNullIfTrue)
2365  if (match(Curr, m_LogicalAnd(m_Value(), m_Value()))) {
2366  for (const auto *CurrU : Curr->users())
2367  if (Visited.insert(CurrU).second)
2368  WorkList.push_back(CurrU);
2369  continue;
2370  }
2371 
2372  if (const BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(Curr)) {
2373  assert(BI->isConditional() && "uses a comparison!");
2374 
2375  BasicBlock *NonNullSuccessor =
2376  BI->getSuccessor(NonNullIfTrue ? 0 : 1);
2377  BasicBlockEdge Edge(BI->getParent(), NonNullSuccessor);
2378  if (Edge.isSingleEdge() && DT->dominates(Edge, CtxI->getParent()))
2379  return true;
2380  } else if (NonNullIfTrue && isGuard(Curr) &&
2381  DT->dominates(cast<Instruction>(Curr), CtxI)) {
2382  return true;
2383  }
2384  }
2385  }
2386  }
2387 
2388  return false;
2389 }
2390 
2391 /// Does the 'Range' metadata (which must be a valid MD_range operand list)
2392 /// ensure that the value it's attached to is never Value? 'RangeType' is
2393 /// is the type of the value described by the range.
2394 static bool rangeMetadataExcludesValue(const MDNode* Ranges, const APInt& Value) {
2395  const unsigned NumRanges = Ranges->getNumOperands() / 2;
2396  assert(NumRanges >= 1);
2397  for (unsigned i = 0; i < NumRanges; ++i) {
2398  ConstantInt *Lower =
2399  mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(Ranges->getOperand(2 * i + 0));
2400  ConstantInt *Upper =
2401  mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(Ranges->getOperand(2 * i + 1));
2402  ConstantRange Range(Lower->getValue(), Upper->getValue());
2403  if (Range.contains(Value))
2404  return false;
2405  }
2406  return true;
2407 }
2408 
2409 /// Try to detect a recurrence that monotonically increases/decreases from a
2410 /// non-zero starting value. These are common as induction variables.
2411 static bool isNonZeroRecurrence(const PHINode *PN) {
2412  BinaryOperator *BO = nullptr;
2413  Value *Start = nullptr, *Step = nullptr;
2414  const APInt *StartC, *StepC;
2415  if (!matchSimpleRecurrence(PN, BO, Start, Step) ||
2416  !match(Start, m_APInt(StartC)) || StartC->isZero())
2417  return false;
2418 
2419  switch (BO->getOpcode()) {
2420  case Instruction::Add:
2421  // Starting from non-zero and stepping away from zero can never wrap back
2422  // to zero.
2423  return BO->hasNoUnsignedWrap() ||
2424  (BO->hasNoSignedWrap() && match(Step, m_APInt(StepC)) &&
2425  StartC->isNegative() == StepC->isNegative());
2426  case Instruction::Mul:
2427  return (BO->hasNoUnsignedWrap() || BO->hasNoSignedWrap()) &&
2428  match(Step, m_APInt(StepC)) && !StepC->isZero();
2429  case Instruction::Shl:
2430  return BO->hasNoUnsignedWrap() || BO->hasNoSignedWrap();
2431  case Instruction::AShr:
2432  case Instruction::LShr:
2433  return BO->isExact();
2434  default:
2435  return false;
2436  }
2437 }
2438 
2439 /// Return true if the given value is known to be non-zero when defined. For
2440 /// vectors, return true if every demanded element is known to be non-zero when
2441 /// defined. For pointers, if the context instruction and dominator tree are
2442 /// specified, perform context-sensitive analysis and return true if the
2443 /// pointer couldn't possibly be null at the specified instruction.
2444 /// Supports values with integer or pointer type and vectors of integers.
2445 bool isKnownNonZero(const Value *V, const APInt &DemandedElts, unsigned Depth,
2446  const Query &Q) {
2447 
2448 #ifndef NDEBUG
2449  Type *Ty = V->getType();
2450  assert(Depth <= MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth && "Limit Search Depth");
2451 
2452  if (auto *FVTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(Ty)) {
2453  assert(
2454  FVTy->getNumElements() == DemandedElts.getBitWidth() &&
2455  "DemandedElt width should equal the fixed vector number of elements");
2456  } else {
2457  assert(DemandedElts == APInt(1, 1) &&
2458  "DemandedElt width should be 1 for scalars");
2459  }
2460 #endif
2461 
2462  if (auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(V)) {
2463  if (C->isNullValue())
2464  return false;
2465  if (isa<ConstantInt>(C))
2466  // Must be non-zero due to null test above.
2467  return true;
2468 
2469  // For constant vectors, check that all elements are undefined or known
2470  // non-zero to determine that the whole vector is known non-zero.
2471  if (auto *VecTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(C->getType())) {
2472  for (unsigned i = 0, e = VecTy->getNumElements(); i != e; ++i) {
2473  if (!DemandedElts[i])
2474  continue;
2475  Constant *Elt = C->getAggregateElement(i);
2476  if (!Elt || Elt->isNullValue())
2477  return false;
2478  if (!isa<UndefValue>(Elt) && !isa<ConstantInt>(Elt))
2479  return false;
2480  }
2481  return true;
2482  }
2483 
2484  // A global variable in address space 0 is non null unless extern weak
2485  // or an absolute symbol reference. Other address spaces may have null as a
2486  // valid address for a global, so we can't assume anything.
2487  if (const GlobalValue *GV = dyn_cast<GlobalValue>(V)) {
2488  if (!GV->isAbsoluteSymbolRef() && !GV->hasExternalWeakLinkage() &&
2489  GV->getType()->getAddressSpace() == 0)
2490  return true;
2491  }
2492 
2493  // For constant expressions, fall through to the Operator code below.
2494  if (!isa<ConstantExpr>(V))
2495  return false;
2496  }
2497 
2498  if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {
2499  if (MDNode *Ranges = Q.IIQ.getMetadata(I, LLVMContext::MD_range)) {
2500  // If the possible ranges don't contain zero, then the value is
2501  // definitely non-zero.
2502  if (auto *Ty = dyn_cast<IntegerType>(V->getType())) {
2503  const APInt ZeroValue(Ty->getBitWidth(), 0);
2504  if (rangeMetadataExcludesValue(Ranges, ZeroValue))
2505  return true;
2506  }
2507  }
2508  }
2509 
2510  if (!isa<Constant>(V) && isKnownNonZeroFromAssume(V, Q))
2511  return true;
2512 
2513  // Some of the tests below are recursive, so bail out if we hit the limit.
2514  if (Depth++ >= MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
2515  return false;
2516 
2517  // Check for pointer simplifications.
2518 
2519  if (PointerType *PtrTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(V->getType())) {
2520  // Alloca never returns null, malloc might.
2521  if (isa<AllocaInst>(V) && Q.DL.getAllocaAddrSpace() == 0)
2522  return true;
2523 
2524  // A byval, inalloca may not be null in a non-default addres space. A
2525  // nonnull argument is assumed never 0.
2526  if (const Argument *A = dyn_cast<Argument>(V)) {
2527  if (((A->hasPassPointeeByValueCopyAttr() &&
2528  !NullPointerIsDefined(A->getParent(), PtrTy->getAddressSpace())) ||
2529  A->hasNonNullAttr()))
2530  return true;
2531  }
2532 
2533  // A Load tagged with nonnull metadata is never null.
2534  if (const LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(V))
2535  if (Q.IIQ.getMetadata(LI, LLVMContext::MD_nonnull))
2536  return true;
2537 
2538  if (const auto *Call = dyn_cast<CallBase>(V)) {
2539  if (Call->isReturnNonNull())
2540  return true;
2541  if (const auto *RP = getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer(Call, true))
2542  return isKnownNonZero(RP, Depth, Q);
2543  }
2544  }
2545 
2546  if (!isa<Constant>(V) &&
2547  isKnownNonNullFromDominatingCondition(V, Q.CxtI, Q.DT))
2548  return true;
2549 
2550  const Operator *I = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
2551  if (!I)
2552  return false;
2553 
2554  unsigned BitWidth = getBitWidth(V->getType()->getScalarType(), Q.DL);
2555  switch (I->getOpcode()) {
2556  case Instruction::GetElementPtr:
2557  if (I->getType()->isPointerTy())
2558  return isGEPKnownNonNull(cast<GEPOperator>(I), Depth, Q);
2559  break;
2560  case Instruction::BitCast:
2561  if (I->getType()->isPointerTy())
2562  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2563  break;
2564  case Instruction::IntToPtr:
2565  // Note that we have to take special care to avoid looking through
2566  // truncating casts, e.g., int2ptr/ptr2int with appropriate sizes, as well
2567  // as casts that can alter the value, e.g., AddrSpaceCasts.
2568  if (!isa<ScalableVectorType>(I->getType()) &&
2569  Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(I->getOperand(0)->getType()).getFixedValue() <=
2570  Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(I->getType()).getFixedValue())
2571  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2572  break;
2573  case Instruction::PtrToInt:
2574  // Similar to int2ptr above, we can look through ptr2int here if the cast
2575  // is a no-op or an extend and not a truncate.
2576  if (!isa<ScalableVectorType>(I->getType()) &&
2577  Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(I->getOperand(0)->getType()).getFixedValue() <=
2578  Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(I->getType()).getFixedValue())
2579  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2580  break;
2581  case Instruction::Or:
2582  // X | Y != 0 if X != 0 or Y != 0.
2583  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Depth, Q) ||
2584  isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(1), DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
2585  case Instruction::SExt:
2586  case Instruction::ZExt:
2587  // ext X != 0 if X != 0.
2588  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2589 
2590  case Instruction::Shl: {
2591  // shl nuw can't remove any non-zero bits.
2592  const OverflowingBinaryOperator *BO = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V);
2593  if (Q.IIQ.hasNoUnsignedWrap(BO))
2594  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2595 
2596  // shl X, Y != 0 if X is odd. Note that the value of the shift is undefined
2597  // if the lowest bit is shifted off the end.
2598  KnownBits Known(BitWidth);
2599  computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Known, Depth, Q);
2600  if (Known.One[0])
2601  return true;
2602  break;
2603  }
2604  case Instruction::LShr:
2605  case Instruction::AShr: {
2606  // shr exact can only shift out zero bits.
2607  const PossiblyExactOperator *BO = cast<PossiblyExactOperator>(V);
2608  if (BO->isExact())
2609  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2610 
2611  // shr X, Y != 0 if X is negative. Note that the value of the shift is not
2612  // defined if the sign bit is shifted off the end.
2613  KnownBits Known =
2614  computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
2615  if (Known.isNegative())
2616  return true;
2617 
2618  // If the shifter operand is a constant, and all of the bits shifted
2619  // out are known to be zero, and X is known non-zero then at least one
2620  // non-zero bit must remain.
2621  if (ConstantInt *Shift = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1))) {
2622  auto ShiftVal = Shift->getLimitedValue(BitWidth - 1);
2623  // Is there a known one in the portion not shifted out?
2624  if (Known.countMaxLeadingZeros() < BitWidth - ShiftVal)
2625  return true;
2626  // Are all the bits to be shifted out known zero?
2627  if (Known.countMinTrailingZeros() >= ShiftVal)
2628  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
2629  }
2630  break;
2631  }
2632  case Instruction::UDiv:
2633  case Instruction::SDiv:
2634  // div exact can only produce a zero if the dividend is zero.
2635  if (cast<PossiblyExactOperator>(I)->isExact())
2636  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
2637  break;
2638  case Instruction::Add: {
2639  // X + Y.
2640  KnownBits XKnown =
2641  computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
2642  KnownBits YKnown =
2643  computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
2644 
2645  // If X and Y are both non-negative (as signed values) then their sum is not
2646  // zero unless both X and Y are zero.
2647  if (XKnown.isNonNegative() && YKnown.isNonNegative())
2648  if (isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Depth, Q) ||
2649  isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(1), DemandedElts, Depth, Q))
2650  return true;
2651 
2652  // If X and Y are both negative (as signed values) then their sum is not
2653  // zero unless both X and Y equal INT_MIN.
2654  if (XKnown.isNegative() && YKnown.isNegative()) {
2655  APInt Mask = APInt::getSignedMaxValue(BitWidth);
2656  // The sign bit of X is set. If some other bit is set then X is not equal
2657  // to INT_MIN.
2658  if (XKnown.One.intersects(Mask))
2659  return true;
2660  // The sign bit of Y is set. If some other bit is set then Y is not equal
2661  // to INT_MIN.
2662  if (YKnown.One.intersects(Mask))
2663  return true;
2664  }
2665 
2666  // The sum of a non-negative number and a power of two is not zero.
2667  if (XKnown.isNonNegative() &&
2668  isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(I->getOperand(1), /*OrZero*/ false, Depth, Q))
2669  return true;
2670  if (YKnown.isNonNegative() &&
2671  isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(I->getOperand(0), /*OrZero*/ false, Depth, Q))
2672  return true;
2673  break;
2674  }
2675  case Instruction::Mul: {
2676  // If X and Y are non-zero then so is X * Y as long as the multiplication
2677  // does not overflow.
2678  const OverflowingBinaryOperator *BO = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V);
2679  if ((Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(BO) || Q.IIQ.hasNoUnsignedWrap(BO)) &&
2680  isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), DemandedElts, Depth, Q) &&
2681  isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(1), DemandedElts, Depth, Q))
2682  return true;
2683  break;
2684  }
2685  case Instruction::Select:
2686  // (C ? X : Y) != 0 if X != 0 and Y != 0.
2687  if (isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(1), DemandedElts, Depth, Q) &&
2688  isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(2), DemandedElts, Depth, Q))
2689  return true;
2690  break;
2691  case Instruction::PHI: {
2692  auto *PN = cast<PHINode>(I);
2693  if (Q.IIQ.UseInstrInfo && isNonZeroRecurrence(PN))
2694  return true;
2695 
2696  // Check if all incoming values are non-zero using recursion.
2697  Query RecQ = Q;
2698  unsigned NewDepth = std::max(Depth, MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth - 1);
2699  return llvm::all_of(PN->operands(), [&](const Use &U) {
2700  if (U.get() == PN)
2701  return true;
2702  RecQ.CxtI = PN->getIncomingBlock(U)->getTerminator();
2703  return isKnownNonZero(U.get(), DemandedElts, NewDepth, RecQ);
2704  });
2705  }
2706  case Instruction::ExtractElement:
2707  if (const auto *EEI = dyn_cast<ExtractElementInst>(V)) {
2708  const Value *Vec = EEI->getVectorOperand();
2709  const Value *Idx = EEI->getIndexOperand();
2710  auto *CIdx = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Idx);
2711  if (auto *VecTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(Vec->getType())) {
2712  unsigned NumElts = VecTy->getNumElements();
2713  APInt DemandedVecElts = APInt::getAllOnes(NumElts);
2714  if (CIdx && CIdx->getValue().ult(NumElts))
2715  DemandedVecElts = APInt::getOneBitSet(NumElts, CIdx->getZExtValue());
2716  return isKnownNonZero(Vec, DemandedVecElts, Depth, Q);
2717  }
2718  }
2719  break;
2720  case Instruction::Freeze:
2721  return isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q) &&
2722  isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(I->getOperand(0), Q.AC, Q.CxtI, Q.DT,
2723  Depth);
2724  case Instruction::Call:
2725  if (cast<CallInst>(I)->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::vscale)
2726  return true;
2727  break;
2728  }
2729 
2730  KnownBits Known(BitWidth);
2731  computeKnownBits(V, DemandedElts, Known, Depth, Q);
2732  return Known.One != 0;
2733 }
2734 
2735 bool isKnownNonZero(const Value* V, unsigned Depth, const Query& Q) {
2736  auto *FVTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(V->getType());
2737  APInt DemandedElts =
2738  FVTy ? APInt::getAllOnes(FVTy->getNumElements()) : APInt(1, 1);
2739  return isKnownNonZero(V, DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
2740 }
2741 
2742 /// If the pair of operators are the same invertible function, return the
2743 /// the operands of the function corresponding to each input. Otherwise,
2744 /// return std::nullopt. An invertible function is one that is 1-to-1 and maps
2745 /// every input value to exactly one output value. This is equivalent to
2746 /// saying that Op1 and Op2 are equal exactly when the specified pair of
2747 /// operands are equal, (except that Op1 and Op2 may be poison more often.)
2748 static std::optional<std::pair<Value*, Value*>>
2749 getInvertibleOperands(const Operator *Op1,
2750  const Operator *Op2) {
2751  if (Op1->getOpcode() != Op2->getOpcode())
2752  return std::nullopt;
2753 
2754  auto getOperands = [&](unsigned OpNum) -> auto {
2755  return std::make_pair(Op1->getOperand(OpNum), Op2->getOperand(OpNum));
2756  };
2757 
2758  switch (Op1->getOpcode()) {
2759  default:
2760  break;
2761  case Instruction::Add:
2762  case Instruction::Sub:
2763  if (Op1->getOperand(0) == Op2->getOperand(0))
2764  return getOperands(1);
2765  if (Op1->getOperand(1) == Op2->getOperand(1))
2766  return getOperands(0);
2767  break;
2768  case Instruction::Mul: {
2769  // invertible if A * B == (A * B) mod 2^N where A, and B are integers
2770  // and N is the bitwdith. The nsw case is non-obvious, but proven by
2771  // alive2: https://alive2.llvm.org/ce/z/Z6D5qK
2772  auto *OBO1 = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(Op1);
2773  auto *OBO2 = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(Op2);
2774  if ((!OBO1->hasNoUnsignedWrap() || !OBO2->hasNoUnsignedWrap()) &&
2775  (!OBO1->hasNoSignedWrap() || !OBO2->hasNoSignedWrap()))
2776  break;
2777 
2778  // Assume operand order has been canonicalized
2779  if (Op1->getOperand(1) == Op2->getOperand(1) &&
2780  isa<ConstantInt>(Op1->getOperand(1)) &&
2781  !cast<ConstantInt>(Op1->getOperand(1))->isZero())
2782  return getOperands(0);
2783  break;
2784  }
2785  case Instruction::Shl: {
2786  // Same as multiplies, with the difference that we don't need to check
2787  // for a non-zero multiply. Shifts always multiply by non-zero.
2788  auto *OBO1 = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(Op1);
2789  auto *OBO2 = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(Op2);
2790  if ((!OBO1->hasNoUnsignedWrap() || !OBO2->hasNoUnsignedWrap()) &&
2791  (!OBO1->hasNoSignedWrap() || !OBO2->hasNoSignedWrap()))
2792  break;
2793 
2794  if (Op1->getOperand(1) == Op2->getOperand(1))
2795  return getOperands(0);
2796  break;
2797  }
2798  case Instruction::AShr:
2799  case Instruction::LShr: {
2800  auto *PEO1 = cast<PossiblyExactOperator>(Op1);
2801  auto *PEO2 = cast<PossiblyExactOperator>(Op2);
2802  if (!PEO1->isExact() || !PEO2->isExact())
2803  break;
2804 
2805  if (Op1->getOperand(1) == Op2->getOperand(1))
2806  return getOperands(0);
2807  break;
2808  }
2809  case Instruction::SExt:
2810  case Instruction::ZExt:
2811  if (Op1->getOperand(0)->getType() == Op2->getOperand(0)->getType())
2812  return getOperands(0);
2813  break;
2814  case Instruction::PHI: {
2815  const PHINode *PN1 = cast<PHINode>(Op1);
2816  const PHINode *PN2 = cast<PHINode>(Op2);
2817 
2818  // If PN1 and PN2 are both recurrences, can we prove the entire recurrences
2819  // are a single invertible function of the start values? Note that repeated
2820  // application of an invertible function is also invertible
2821  BinaryOperator *BO1 = nullptr;
2822  Value *Start1 = nullptr, *Step1 = nullptr;
2823  BinaryOperator *BO2 = nullptr;
2824  Value *Start2 = nullptr, *Step2 = nullptr;
2825  if (PN1->getParent() != PN2->getParent() ||
2826  !matchSimpleRecurrence(PN1, BO1, Start1, Step1) ||
2827  !matchSimpleRecurrence(PN2, BO2, Start2, Step2))
2828  break;
2829 
2830  auto Values = getInvertibleOperands(cast<Operator>(BO1),
2831  cast<Operator>(BO2));
2832  if (!Values)
2833  break;
2834 
2835  // We have to be careful of mutually defined recurrences here. Ex:
2836  // * X_i = X_(i-1) OP Y_(i-1), and Y_i = X_(i-1) OP V
2837  // * X_i = Y_i = X_(i-1) OP Y_(i-1)
2838  // The invertibility of these is complicated, and not worth reasoning
2839  // about (yet?).
2840  if (Values->first != PN1 || Values->second != PN2)
2841  break;
2842 
2843  return std::make_pair(Start1, Start2);
2844  }
2845  }
2846  return std::nullopt;
2847 }
2848 
2849 /// Return true if V2 == V1 + X, where X is known non-zero.
2850 static bool isAddOfNonZero(const Value *V1, const Value *V2, unsigned Depth,
2851  const Query &Q) {
2852  const BinaryOperator *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(V1);
2853  if (!BO || BO->getOpcode() != Instruction::Add)
2854  return false;
2855  Value *Op = nullptr;
2856  if (V2 == BO->getOperand(0))
2857  Op = BO->getOperand(1);
2858  else if (V2 == BO->getOperand(1))
2859  Op = BO->getOperand(0);
2860  else
2861  return false;
2862  return isKnownNonZero(Op, Depth + 1, Q);
2863 }
2864 
2865 /// Return true if V2 == V1 * C, where V1 is known non-zero, C is not 0/1 and
2866 /// the multiplication is nuw or nsw.
2867 static bool isNonEqualMul(const Value *V1, const Value *V2, unsigned Depth,
2868  const Query &Q) {
2869  if (auto *OBO = dyn_cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V2)) {
2870  const APInt *C;
2871  return match(OBO, m_Mul(m_Specific(V1), m_APInt(C))) &&
2872  (OBO->hasNoUnsignedWrap() || OBO->hasNoSignedWrap()) &&
2873  !C->isZero() && !C->isOne() && isKnownNonZero(V1, Depth + 1, Q);
2874  }
2875  return false;
2876 }
2877 
2878 /// Return true if V2 == V1 << C, where V1 is known non-zero, C is not 0 and
2879 /// the shift is nuw or nsw.
2880 static bool isNonEqualShl(const Value *V1, const Value *V2, unsigned Depth,
2881  const Query &Q) {
2882  if (auto *OBO = dyn_cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V2)) {
2883  const APInt *C;
2884  return match(OBO, m_Shl(m_Specific(V1), m_APInt(C))) &&
2885  (OBO->hasNoUnsignedWrap() || OBO->hasNoSignedWrap()) &&
2886  !C->isZero() && isKnownNonZero(V1, Depth + 1, Q);
2887  }
2888  return false;
2889 }
2890 
2891 static bool isNonEqualPHIs(const PHINode *PN1, const PHINode *PN2,
2892  unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
2893  // Check two PHIs are in same block.
2894  if (PN1->getParent() != PN2->getParent())
2895  return false;
2896 
2897  SmallPtrSet<const BasicBlock *, 8> VisitedBBs;
2898  bool UsedFullRecursion = false;
2899  for (const BasicBlock *IncomBB : PN1->blocks()) {
2900  if (!VisitedBBs.insert(IncomBB).second)
2901  continue; // Don't reprocess blocks that we have dealt with already.
2902  const Value *IV1 = PN1->getIncomingValueForBlock(IncomBB);
2903  const Value *IV2 = PN2->getIncomingValueForBlock(IncomBB);
2904  const APInt *C1, *C2;
2905  if (match(IV1, m_APInt(C1)) && match(IV2, m_APInt(C2)) && *C1 != *C2)
2906  continue;
2907 
2908  // Only one pair of phi operands is allowed for full recursion.
2909  if (UsedFullRecursion)
2910  return false;
2911 
2912  Query RecQ = Q;
2913  RecQ.CxtI = IncomBB->getTerminator();
2914  if (!isKnownNonEqual(IV1, IV2, Depth + 1, RecQ))
2915  return false;
2916  UsedFullRecursion = true;
2917  }
2918  return true;
2919 }
2920 
2921 /// Return true if it is known that V1 != V2.
2922 static bool isKnownNonEqual(const Value *V1, const Value *V2, unsigned Depth,
2923  const Query &Q) {
2924  if (V1 == V2)
2925  return false;
2926  if (V1->getType() != V2->getType())
2927  // We can't look through casts yet.
2928  return false;
2929 
2930  if (Depth >= MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
2931  return false;
2932 
2933  // See if we can recurse through (exactly one of) our operands. This
2934  // requires our operation be 1-to-1 and map every input value to exactly
2935  // one output value. Such an operation is invertible.
2936  auto *O1 = dyn_cast<Operator>(V1);
2937  auto *O2 = dyn_cast<Operator>(V2);
2938  if (O1 && O2 && O1->getOpcode() == O2->getOpcode()) {
2939  if (auto Values = getInvertibleOperands(O1, O2))
2940  return isKnownNonEqual(Values->first, Values->second, Depth + 1, Q);
2941 
2942  if (const PHINode *PN1 = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V1)) {
2943  const PHINode *PN2 = cast<PHINode>(V2);
2944  // FIXME: This is missing a generalization to handle the case where one is
2945  // a PHI and another one isn't.
2946  if (isNonEqualPHIs(PN1, PN2, Depth, Q))
2947  return true;
2948  };
2949  }
2950 
2951  if (isAddOfNonZero(V1, V2, Depth, Q) || isAddOfNonZero(V2, V1, Depth, Q))
2952  return true;
2953 
2954  if (isNonEqualMul(V1, V2, Depth, Q) || isNonEqualMul(V2, V1, Depth, Q))
2955  return true;
2956 
2957  if (isNonEqualShl(V1, V2, Depth, Q) || isNonEqualShl(V2, V1, Depth, Q))
2958  return true;
2959 
2960  if (V1->getType()->isIntOrIntVectorTy()) {
2961  // Are any known bits in V1 contradictory to known bits in V2? If V1
2962  // has a known zero where V2 has a known one, they must not be equal.
2963  KnownBits Known1 = computeKnownBits(V1, Depth, Q);
2964  KnownBits Known2 = computeKnownBits(V2, Depth, Q);
2965 
2966  if (Known1.Zero.intersects(Known2.One) ||
2967  Known2.Zero.intersects(Known1.One))
2968  return true;
2969  }
2970  return false;
2971 }
2972 
2973 /// Return true if 'V & Mask' is known to be zero. We use this predicate to
2974 /// simplify operations downstream. Mask is known to be zero for bits that V
2975 /// cannot have.
2976 ///
2977 /// This function is defined on values with integer type, values with pointer
2978 /// type, and vectors of integers. In the case
2979 /// where V is a vector, the mask, known zero, and known one values are the
2980 /// same width as the vector element, and the bit is set only if it is true
2981 /// for all of the elements in the vector.
2982 bool MaskedValueIsZero(const Value *V, const APInt &Mask, unsigned Depth,
2983  const Query &Q) {
2984  KnownBits Known(Mask.getBitWidth());
2985  computeKnownBits(V, Known, Depth, Q);
2986  return Mask.isSubsetOf(Known.Zero);
2987 }
2988 
2989 // Match a signed min+max clamp pattern like smax(smin(In, CHigh), CLow).
2990 // Returns the input and lower/upper bounds.
2991 static bool isSignedMinMaxClamp(const Value *Select, const Value *&In,
2992  const APInt *&CLow, const APInt *&CHigh) {
2993  assert(isa<Operator>(Select) &&
2994  cast<Operator>(Select)->getOpcode() == Instruction::Select &&
2995  "Input should be a Select!");
2996 
2997  const Value *LHS = nullptr, *RHS = nullptr;
2998  SelectPatternFlavor SPF = matchSelectPattern(Select, LHS, RHS).Flavor;
2999  if (SPF != SPF_SMAX && SPF != SPF_SMIN)
3000  return false;
3001 
3002  if (!match(RHS, m_APInt(CLow)))
3003  return false;
3004 
3005  const Value *LHS2 = nullptr, *RHS2 = nullptr;
3006  SelectPatternFlavor SPF2 = matchSelectPattern(LHS, LHS2, RHS2).Flavor;
3007  if (getInverseMinMaxFlavor(SPF) != SPF2)
3008  return false;
3009 
3010  if (!match(RHS2, m_APInt(CHigh)))
3011  return false;
3012 
3013  if (SPF == SPF_SMIN)
3014  std::swap(CLow, CHigh);
3015 
3016  In = LHS2;
3017  return CLow->sle(*CHigh);
3018 }
3019 
3020 static bool isSignedMinMaxIntrinsicClamp(const IntrinsicInst *II,
3021  const APInt *&CLow,
3022  const APInt *&CHigh) {
3023  assert((II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::smin ||
3024  II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::smax) && "Must be smin/smax");
3025 
3026  Intrinsic::ID InverseID = getInverseMinMaxIntrinsic(II->getIntrinsicID());
3027  auto *InnerII = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(II->getArgOperand(0));
3028  if (!InnerII || InnerII->getIntrinsicID() != InverseID ||
3029  !match(II->getArgOperand(1), m_APInt(CLow)) ||
3030  !match(InnerII->getArgOperand(1), m_APInt(CHigh)))
3031  return false;
3032 
3033  if (II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::smin)
3034  std::swap(CLow, CHigh);
3035  return CLow->sle(*CHigh);
3036 }
3037 
3038 /// For vector constants, loop over the elements and find the constant with the
3039 /// minimum number of sign bits. Return 0 if the value is not a vector constant
3040 /// or if any element was not analyzed; otherwise, return the count for the
3041 /// element with the minimum number of sign bits.
3042 static unsigned computeNumSignBitsVectorConstant(const Value *V,
3043  const APInt &DemandedElts,
3044  unsigned TyBits) {
3045  const auto *CV = dyn_cast<Constant>(V);
3046  if (!CV || !isa<FixedVectorType>(CV->getType()))
3047  return 0;
3048 
3049  unsigned MinSignBits = TyBits;
3050  unsigned NumElts = cast<FixedVectorType>(CV->getType())->getNumElements();
3051  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
3052  if (!DemandedElts[i])
3053  continue;
3054  // If we find a non-ConstantInt, bail out.
3055  auto *Elt = dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(CV->getAggregateElement(i));
3056  if (!Elt)
3057  return 0;
3058 
3059  MinSignBits = std::min(MinSignBits, Elt->getValue().getNumSignBits());
3060  }
3061 
3062  return MinSignBits;
3063 }
3064 
3065 static unsigned ComputeNumSignBitsImpl(const Value *V,
3066  const APInt &DemandedElts,
3067  unsigned Depth, const Query &Q);
3068 
3069 static unsigned ComputeNumSignBits(const Value *V, const APInt &DemandedElts,
3070  unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
3071  unsigned Result = ComputeNumSignBitsImpl(V, DemandedElts, Depth, Q);
3072  assert(Result > 0 && "At least one sign bit needs to be present!");
3073  return Result;
3074 }
3075 
3076 /// Return the number of times the sign bit of the register is replicated into
3077 /// the other bits. We know that at least 1 bit is always equal to the sign bit
3078 /// (itself), but other cases can give us information. For example, immediately
3079 /// after an "ashr X, 2", we know that the top 3 bits are all equal to each
3080 /// other, so we return 3. For vectors, return the number of sign bits for the
3081 /// vector element with the minimum number of known sign bits of the demanded
3082 /// elements in the vector specified by DemandedElts.
3083 static unsigned ComputeNumSignBitsImpl(const Value *V,
3084  const APInt &DemandedElts,
3085  unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
3086  Type *Ty = V->getType();
3087 #ifndef NDEBUG
3088  assert(Depth <= MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth && "Limit Search Depth");
3089 
3090  if (auto *FVTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(Ty)) {
3091  assert(
3092  FVTy->getNumElements() == DemandedElts.getBitWidth() &&
3093  "DemandedElt width should equal the fixed vector number of elements");
3094  } else {
3095  assert(DemandedElts == APInt(1, 1) &&
3096  "DemandedElt width should be 1 for scalars");
3097  }
3098 #endif
3099 
3100  // We return the minimum number of sign bits that are guaranteed to be present
3101  // in V, so for undef we have to conservatively return 1. We don't have the
3102  // same behavior for poison though -- that's a FIXME today.
3103 
3104  Type *ScalarTy = Ty->getScalarType();
3105  unsigned TyBits = ScalarTy->isPointerTy() ?
3106  Q.DL.getPointerTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy) :
3107  Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy);
3108 
3109  unsigned Tmp, Tmp2;
3110  unsigned FirstAnswer = 1;
3111 
3112  // Note that ConstantInt is handled by the general computeKnownBits case
3113  // below.
3114 
3115  if (Depth == MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
3116  return 1;
3117 
3118  if (auto *U = dyn_cast<Operator>(V)) {
3119  switch (Operator::getOpcode(V)) {
3120  default: break;
3121  case Instruction::SExt:
3122  Tmp = TyBits - U->getOperand(0)->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
3123  return ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q) + Tmp;
3124 
3125  case Instruction::SDiv: {
3126  const APInt *Denominator;
3127  // sdiv X, C -> adds log(C) sign bits.
3128  if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(Denominator))) {
3129 
3130  // Ignore non-positive denominator.
3131  if (!Denominator->isStrictlyPositive())
3132  break;
3133 
3134  // Calculate the incoming numerator bits.
3135  unsigned NumBits = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3136 
3137  // Add floor(log(C)) bits to the numerator bits.
3138  return std::min(TyBits, NumBits + Denominator->logBase2());
3139  }
3140  break;
3141  }
3142 
3143  case Instruction::SRem: {
3144  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3145 
3146  const APInt *Denominator;
3147  // srem X, C -> we know that the result is within [-C+1,C) when C is a
3148  // positive constant. This let us put a lower bound on the number of sign
3149  // bits.
3150  if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(Denominator))) {
3151 
3152  // Ignore non-positive denominator.
3153  if (Denominator->isStrictlyPositive()) {
3154  // Calculate the leading sign bit constraints by examining the
3155  // denominator. Given that the denominator is positive, there are two
3156  // cases:
3157  //
3158  // 1. The numerator is positive. The result range is [0,C) and
3159  // [0,C) u< (1 << ceilLogBase2(C)).
3160  //
3161  // 2. The numerator is negative. Then the result range is (-C,0] and
3162  // integers in (-C,0] are either 0 or >u (-1 << ceilLogBase2(C)).
3163  //
3164  // Thus a lower bound on the number of sign bits is `TyBits -
3165  // ceilLogBase2(C)`.
3166 
3167  unsigned ResBits = TyBits - Denominator->ceilLogBase2();
3168  Tmp = std::max(Tmp, ResBits);
3169  }
3170  }
3171  return Tmp;
3172  }
3173 
3174  case Instruction::AShr: {
3175  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3176  // ashr X, C -> adds C sign bits. Vectors too.
3177  const APInt *ShAmt;
3178  if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(ShAmt))) {
3179  if (ShAmt->uge(TyBits))
3180  break; // Bad shift.
3181  unsigned ShAmtLimited = ShAmt->getZExtValue();
3182  Tmp += ShAmtLimited;
3183  if (Tmp > TyBits) Tmp = TyBits;
3184  }
3185  return Tmp;
3186  }
3187  case Instruction::Shl: {
3188  const APInt *ShAmt;
3189  if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(ShAmt))) {
3190  // shl destroys sign bits.
3191  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3192  if (ShAmt->uge(TyBits) || // Bad shift.
3193  ShAmt->uge(Tmp)) break; // Shifted all sign bits out.
3194  Tmp2 = ShAmt->getZExtValue();
3195  return Tmp - Tmp2;
3196  }
3197  break;
3198  }
3199  case Instruction::And:
3200  case Instruction::Or:
3201  case Instruction::Xor: // NOT is handled here.
3202  // Logical binary ops preserve the number of sign bits at the worst.
3203  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3204  if (Tmp != 1) {
3205  Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
3206  FirstAnswer = std::min(Tmp, Tmp2);
3207  // We computed what we know about the sign bits as our first
3208  // answer. Now proceed to the generic code that uses
3209  // computeKnownBits, and pick whichever answer is better.
3210  }
3211  break;
3212 
3213  case Instruction::Select: {
3214  // If we have a clamp pattern, we know that the number of sign bits will
3215  // be the minimum of the clamp min/max range.
3216  const Value *X;
3217  const APInt *CLow, *CHigh;
3218  if (isSignedMinMaxClamp(U, X, CLow, CHigh))
3219  return std::min(CLow->getNumSignBits(), CHigh->getNumSignBits());
3220 
3221  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
3222  if (Tmp == 1) break;
3223  Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(2), Depth + 1, Q);
3224  return std::min(Tmp, Tmp2);
3225  }
3226 
3227  case Instruction::Add:
3228  // Add can have at most one carry bit. Thus we know that the output
3229  // is, at worst, one more bit than the inputs.
3230  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3231  if (Tmp == 1) break;
3232 
3233  // Special case decrementing a value (ADD X, -1):
3234  if (const auto *CRHS = dyn_cast<Constant>(U->getOperand(1)))
3235  if (CRHS->isAllOnesValue()) {
3236  KnownBits Known(TyBits);
3237  computeKnownBits(U->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
3238 
3239  // If the input is known to be 0 or 1, the output is 0/-1, which is
3240  // all sign bits set.
3241  if ((Known.Zero | 1).isAllOnes())
3242  return TyBits;
3243 
3244  // If we are subtracting one from a positive number, there is no carry
3245  // out of the result.
3246  if (Known.isNonNegative())
3247  return Tmp;
3248  }
3249 
3250  Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
3251  if (Tmp2 == 1) break;
3252  return std::min(Tmp, Tmp2) - 1;
3253 
3254  case Instruction::Sub:
3255  Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
3256  if (Tmp2 == 1) break;
3257 
3258  // Handle NEG.
3259  if (const auto *CLHS = dyn_cast<Constant>(U->getOperand(0)))
3260  if (CLHS->isNullValue()) {
3261  KnownBits Known(TyBits);
3262  computeKnownBits(U->getOperand(1), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
3263  // If the input is known to be 0 or 1, the output is 0/-1, which is
3264  // all sign bits set.
3265  if ((Known.Zero | 1).isAllOnes())
3266  return TyBits;
3267 
3268  // If the input is known to be positive (the sign bit is known clear),
3269  // the output of the NEG has the same number of sign bits as the
3270  // input.
3271  if (Known.isNonNegative())
3272  return Tmp2;
3273 
3274  // Otherwise, we treat this like a SUB.
3275  }
3276 
3277  // Sub can have at most one carry bit. Thus we know that the output
3278  // is, at worst, one more bit than the inputs.
3279  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3280  if (Tmp == 1) break;
3281  return std::min(Tmp, Tmp2) - 1;
3282 
3283  case Instruction::Mul: {
3284  // The output of the Mul can be at most twice the valid bits in the
3285  // inputs.
3286  unsigned SignBitsOp0 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3287  if (SignBitsOp0 == 1) break;
3288  unsigned SignBitsOp1 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
3289  if (SignBitsOp1 == 1) break;
3290  unsigned OutValidBits =
3291  (TyBits - SignBitsOp0 + 1) + (TyBits - SignBitsOp1 + 1);
3292  return OutValidBits > TyBits ? 1 : TyBits - OutValidBits + 1;
3293  }
3294 
3295  case Instruction::PHI: {
3296  const PHINode *PN = cast<PHINode>(U);
3297  unsigned NumIncomingValues = PN->getNumIncomingValues();
3298  // Don't analyze large in-degree PHIs.
3299  if (NumIncomingValues > 4) break;
3300  // Unreachable blocks may have zero-operand PHI nodes.
3301  if (NumIncomingValues == 0) break;
3302 
3303  // Take the minimum of all incoming values. This can't infinitely loop
3304  // because of our depth threshold.
3305  Query RecQ = Q;
3306  Tmp = TyBits;
3307  for (unsigned i = 0, e = NumIncomingValues; i != e; ++i) {
3308  if (Tmp == 1) return Tmp;
3309  RecQ.CxtI = PN->getIncomingBlock(i)->getTerminator();
3310  Tmp = std::min(
3311  Tmp, ComputeNumSignBits(PN->getIncomingValue(i), Depth + 1, RecQ));
3312  }
3313  return Tmp;
3314  }
3315 
3316  case Instruction::Trunc: {
3317  // If the input contained enough sign bits that some remain after the
3318  // truncation, then we can make use of that. Otherwise we don't know
3319  // anything.
3320  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3321  unsigned OperandTyBits = U->getOperand(0)->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
3322  if (Tmp > (OperandTyBits - TyBits))
3323  return Tmp - (OperandTyBits - TyBits);
3324 
3325  return 1;
3326  }
3327 
3328  case Instruction::ExtractElement:
3329  // Look through extract element. At the moment we keep this simple and
3330  // skip tracking the specific element. But at least we might find
3331  // information valid for all elements of the vector (for example if vector
3332  // is sign extended, shifted, etc).
3333  return ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3334 
3335  case Instruction::ShuffleVector: {
3336  // Collect the minimum number of sign bits that are shared by every vector
3337  // element referenced by the shuffle.
3338  auto *Shuf = dyn_cast<ShuffleVectorInst>(U);
3339  if (!Shuf) {
3340  // FIXME: Add support for shufflevector constant expressions.
3341  return 1;
3342  }
3343  APInt DemandedLHS, DemandedRHS;
3344  // For undef elements, we don't know anything about the common state of
3345  // the shuffle result.
3346  if (!getShuffleDemandedElts(Shuf, DemandedElts, DemandedLHS, DemandedRHS))
3347  return 1;
3348  Tmp = std::numeric_limits<unsigned>::max();
3349  if (!!DemandedLHS) {
3350  const Value *LHS = Shuf->getOperand(0);
3351  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(LHS, DemandedLHS, Depth + 1, Q);
3352  }
3353  // If we don't know anything, early out and try computeKnownBits
3354  // fall-back.
3355  if (Tmp == 1)
3356  break;
3357  if (!!DemandedRHS) {
3358  const Value *RHS = Shuf->getOperand(1);
3359  Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(RHS, DemandedRHS, Depth + 1, Q);
3360  Tmp = std::min(Tmp, Tmp2);
3361  }
3362  // If we don't know anything, early out and try computeKnownBits
3363  // fall-back.
3364  if (Tmp == 1)
3365  break;
3366  assert(Tmp <= TyBits && "Failed to determine minimum sign bits");
3367  return Tmp;
3368  }
3369  case Instruction::Call: {
3370  if (const auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(U)) {
3371  switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
3372  default: break;
3373  case Intrinsic::abs:
3374  Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
3375  if (Tmp == 1) break;
3376 
3377  // Absolute value reduces number of sign bits by at most 1.
3378  return Tmp - 1;
3379  case Intrinsic::smin:
3380  case Intrinsic::smax: {
3381  const APInt *CLow, *CHigh;
3382  if (isSignedMinMaxIntrinsicClamp(II, CLow, CHigh))
3383  return std::min(CLow->getNumSignBits(), CHigh->getNumSignBits());
3384  }
3385  }
3386  }
3387  }
3388  }
3389  }
3390 
3391  // Finally, if we can prove that the top bits of the result are 0's or 1's,
3392  // use this information.
3393 
3394  // If we can examine all elements of a vector constant successfully, we're
3395  // done (we can't do any better than that). If not, keep trying.
3396  if (unsigned VecSignBits =
3397  computeNumSignBitsVectorConstant(V, DemandedElts, TyBits))
3398  return VecSignBits;
3399 
3400  KnownBits Known(TyBits);
3401  computeKnownBits(V, DemandedElts, Known, Depth, Q);
3402 
3403  // If we know that the sign bit is either zero or one, determine the number of
3404  // identical bits in the top of the input value.
3405  return std::max(FirstAnswer, Known.countMinSignBits());
3406 }
3407 
3408 Intrinsic::ID llvm::getIntrinsicForCallSite(const CallBase &CB,
3409  const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
3410  const Function *F = CB.getCalledFunction();
3411  if (!F)
3412  return Intrinsic::not_intrinsic;
3413 
3414  if (F->isIntrinsic())
3415  return F->getIntrinsicID();
3416 
3417  // We are going to infer semantics of a library function based on mapping it
3418  // to an LLVM intrinsic. Check that the library function is available from
3419  // this callbase and in this environment.
3420  LibFunc Func;
3421  if (F->hasLocalLinkage() || !TLI || !TLI->getLibFunc(CB, Func) ||
3422  !CB.onlyReadsMemory())
3423  return Intrinsic::not_intrinsic;
3424 
3425  switch (Func) {
3426  default:
3427  break;
3428  case LibFunc_sin:
3429  case LibFunc_sinf:
3430  case LibFunc_sinl:
3431  return Intrinsic::sin;
3432  case LibFunc_cos:
3433  case LibFunc_cosf:
3434  case LibFunc_cosl:
3435  return Intrinsic::cos;
3436  case LibFunc_exp:
3437  case LibFunc_expf:
3438  case LibFunc_expl:
3439  return Intrinsic::exp;
3440  case LibFunc_exp2:
3441  case LibFunc_exp2f:
3442  case LibFunc_exp2l:
3443  return Intrinsic::exp2;
3444  case LibFunc_log:
3445  case LibFunc_logf:
3446  case LibFunc_logl:
3447  return Intrinsic::log;
3448  case LibFunc_log10:
3449  case LibFunc_log10f:
3450  case LibFunc_log10l:
3451  return Intrinsic::log10;
3452  case LibFunc_log2:
3453  case LibFunc_log2f:
3454  case LibFunc_log2l:
3455  return Intrinsic::log2;
3456  case LibFunc_fabs:
3457  case LibFunc_fabsf:
3458  case LibFunc_fabsl:
3459  return Intrinsic::fabs;
3460  case LibFunc_fmin:
3461  case LibFunc_fminf:
3462  case LibFunc_fminl:
3463  return Intrinsic::minnum;
3464  case LibFunc_fmax:
3465  case LibFunc_fmaxf:
3466  case LibFunc_fmaxl:
3467  return Intrinsic::maxnum;
3468  case LibFunc_copysign:
3469  case LibFunc_copysignf:
3470  case LibFunc_copysignl:
3471  return Intrinsic::copysign;
3472  case LibFunc_floor:
3473  case LibFunc_floorf:
3474  case LibFunc_floorl:
3475  return Intrinsic::floor;
3476  case LibFunc_ceil:
3477  case LibFunc_ceilf:
3478  case LibFunc_ceill:
3479  return Intrinsic::ceil;
3480  case LibFunc_trunc:
3481  case LibFunc_truncf:
3482  case LibFunc_truncl:
3483  return Intrinsic::trunc;
3484  case LibFunc_rint:
3485  case LibFunc_rintf:
3486  case LibFunc_rintl:
3487  return Intrinsic::rint;
3488  case LibFunc_nearbyint:
3489  case LibFunc_nearbyintf:
3490  case LibFunc_nearbyintl:
3491  return Intrinsic::nearbyint;
3492  case LibFunc_round:
3493  case LibFunc_roundf:
3494  case LibFunc_roundl:
3495  return Intrinsic::round;
3496  case LibFunc_roundeven:
3497  case LibFunc_roundevenf:
3498  case LibFunc_roundevenl:
3499  return Intrinsic::roundeven;
3500  case LibFunc_pow:
3501  case LibFunc_powf:
3502  case LibFunc_powl:
3503  return Intrinsic::pow;
3504  case LibFunc_sqrt:
3505  case LibFunc_sqrtf:
3506  case LibFunc_sqrtl:
3507  return Intrinsic::sqrt;
3508  }
3509 
3510  return Intrinsic::not_intrinsic;
3511 }
3512 
3513 /// Return true if we can prove that the specified FP value is never equal to
3514 /// -0.0.
3515 /// NOTE: Do not check 'nsz' here because that fast-math-flag does not guarantee
3516 /// that a value is not -0.0. It only guarantees that -0.0 may be treated
3517 /// the same as +0.0 in floating-point ops.
3518 bool llvm::CannotBeNegativeZero(const Value *V, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI,
3519  unsigned Depth) {
3520  if (auto *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(V))
3521  return !CFP->getValueAPF().isNegZero();
3522 
3523  if (Depth == MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
3524  return false;
3525 
3526  auto *Op = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
3527  if (!Op)
3528  return false;
3529 
3530  // (fadd x, 0.0) is guaranteed to return +0.0, not -0.0.
3531  if (match(Op, m_FAdd(m_Value(), m_PosZeroFP())))
3532  return true;
3533 
3534  // sitofp and uitofp turn into +0.0 for zero.
3535  if (isa<SIToFPInst>(Op) || isa<UIToFPInst>(Op))
3536  return true;
3537 
3538  if (auto *Call = dyn_cast<CallInst>(Op)) {
3539  Intrinsic::ID IID = getIntrinsicForCallSite(*Call, TLI);
3540  switch (IID) {
3541  default:
3542  break;
3543  // sqrt(-0.0) = -0.0, no other negative results are possible.
3544  case Intrinsic::sqrt:
3545  case Intrinsic::canonicalize:
3546  return CannotBeNegativeZero(Call->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3547  case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_sqrt: {
3548  // NOTE: This rounding mode restriction may be too strict.
3549  const auto *CI = cast<ConstrainedFPIntrinsic>(Call);
3550  if (CI->getRoundingMode() == RoundingMode::NearestTiesToEven)
3551  return CannotBeNegativeZero(Call->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3552  else
3553  return false;
3554  }
3555  // fabs(x) != -0.0
3556  case Intrinsic::fabs:
3557  return true;
3558  // sitofp and uitofp turn into +0.0 for zero.
3559  case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_sitofp:
3560  case Intrinsic::experimental_constrained_uitofp:
3561  return true;
3562  }
3563  }
3564 
3565  return false;
3566 }
3567 
3568 /// If \p SignBitOnly is true, test for a known 0 sign bit rather than a
3569 /// standard ordered compare. e.g. make -0.0 olt 0.0 be true because of the sign
3570 /// bit despite comparing equal.
3571 static bool cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(const Value *V,
3572  const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI,
3573  bool SignBitOnly,
3574  unsigned Depth) {
3575  // TODO: This function does not do the right thing when SignBitOnly is true
3576  // and we're lowering to a hypothetical IEEE 754-compliant-but-evil platform
3577  // which flips the sign bits of NaNs. See
3578  // https://llvm.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=31702.
3579 
3580  if (const ConstantFP *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(V)) {
3581  return !CFP->getValueAPF().isNegative() ||
3582  (!SignBitOnly && CFP->getValueAPF().isZero());
3583  }
3584 
3585  // Handle vector of constants.
3586  if (auto *CV = dyn_cast<Constant>(V)) {
3587  if (auto *CVFVTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(CV->getType())) {
3588  unsigned NumElts = CVFVTy->getNumElements();
3589  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
3590  auto *CFP = dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantFP>(CV->getAggregateElement(i));
3591  if (!CFP)
3592  return false;
3593  if (CFP->getValueAPF().isNegative() &&
3594  (SignBitOnly || !CFP->getValueAPF().isZero()))
3595  return false;
3596  }
3597 
3598  // All non-negative ConstantFPs.
3599  return true;
3600  }
3601  }
3602 
3603  if (Depth == MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
3604  return false;
3605 
3606  const Operator *I = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
3607  if (!I)
3608  return false;
3609 
3610  switch (I->getOpcode()) {
3611  default:
3612  break;
3613  // Unsigned integers are always nonnegative.
3614  case Instruction::UIToFP:
3615  return true;
3616  case Instruction::FDiv:
3617  // X / X is always exactly 1.0 or a NaN.
3618  if (I->getOperand(0) == I->getOperand(1) &&
3619  (!SignBitOnly || cast<FPMathOperator>(I)->hasNoNaNs()))
3620  return true;
3621 
3622  // Set SignBitOnly for RHS, because X / -0.0 is -Inf (or NaN).
3623  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3624  Depth + 1) &&
3625  cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI,
3626  /*SignBitOnly*/ true, Depth + 1);
3627  case Instruction::FMul:
3628  // X * X is always non-negative or a NaN.
3629  if (I->getOperand(0) == I->getOperand(1) &&
3630  (!SignBitOnly || cast<FPMathOperator>(I)->hasNoNaNs()))
3631  return true;
3632 
3633  [[fallthrough]];
3634  case Instruction::FAdd:
3635  case Instruction::FRem:
3636  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3637  Depth + 1) &&
3638  cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3639  Depth + 1);
3640  case Instruction::Select:
3641  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3642  Depth + 1) &&
3643  cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(2), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3644  Depth + 1);
3645  case Instruction::FPExt:
3646  case Instruction::FPTrunc:
3647  // Widening/narrowing never change sign.
3648  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3649  Depth + 1);
3650  case Instruction::ExtractElement:
3651  // Look through extract element. At the moment we keep this simple and skip
3652  // tracking the specific element. But at least we might find information
3653  // valid for all elements of the vector.
3654  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3655  Depth + 1);
3656  case Instruction::Call:
3657  const auto *CI = cast<CallInst>(I);
3658  Intrinsic::ID IID = getIntrinsicForCallSite(*CI, TLI);
3659  switch (IID) {
3660  default:
3661  break;
3662  case Intrinsic::canonicalize:
3663  case Intrinsic::arithmetic_fence:
3664  case Intrinsic::floor:
3665  case Intrinsic::ceil:
3666  case Intrinsic::trunc:
3667  case Intrinsic::rint:
3668  case Intrinsic::nearbyint:
3669  case Intrinsic::round:
3670  case Intrinsic::roundeven:
3671  case Intrinsic::fptrunc_round:
3672  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly, Depth + 1);
3673  case Intrinsic::maxnum: {
3674  Value *V0 = I->getOperand(0), *V1 = I->getOperand(1);
3675  auto isPositiveNum = [&](Value *V) {
3676  if (SignBitOnly) {
3677  // With SignBitOnly, this is tricky because the result of
3678  // maxnum(+0.0, -0.0) is unspecified. Just check if the operand is
3679  // a constant strictly greater than 0.0.
3680  const APFloat *C;
3681  return match(V, m_APFloat(C)) &&
3682  *C > APFloat::getZero(C->getSemantics());
3683  }
3684 
3685  // -0.0 compares equal to 0.0, so if this operand is at least -0.0,
3686  // maxnum can't be ordered-less-than-zero.
3687  return isKnownNeverNaN(V, TLI) &&
3688  cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(V, TLI, false, Depth + 1);
3689  };
3690 
3691  // TODO: This could be improved. We could also check that neither operand
3692  // has its sign bit set (and at least 1 is not-NAN?).
3693  return isPositiveNum(V0) || isPositiveNum(V1);
3694  }
3695 
3696  case Intrinsic::maximum:
3697  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3698  Depth + 1) ||
3699  cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3700  Depth + 1);
3701  case Intrinsic::minnum:
3702  case Intrinsic::minimum:
3703  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3704  Depth + 1) &&
3705  cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3706  Depth + 1);
3707  case Intrinsic::exp:
3708  case Intrinsic::exp2:
3709  case Intrinsic::fabs:
3710  return true;
3711  case Intrinsic::copysign:
3712  // Only the sign operand matters.
3713  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, true,
3714  Depth + 1);
3715  case Intrinsic::sqrt:
3716  // sqrt(x) is always >= -0 or NaN. Moreover, sqrt(x) == -0 iff x == -0.
3717  if (!SignBitOnly)
3718  return true;
3719  return CI->hasNoNaNs() && (CI->hasNoSignedZeros() ||
3720  CannotBeNegativeZero(CI->getOperand(0), TLI));
3721 
3722  case Intrinsic::powi:
3723  if (ConstantInt *Exponent = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1))) {
3724  // powi(x,n) is non-negative if n is even.
3725  if (Exponent->getBitWidth() <= 64 && Exponent->getSExtValue() % 2u == 0)
3726  return true;
3727  }
3728  // TODO: This is not correct. Given that exp is an integer, here are the
3729  // ways that pow can return a negative value:
3730  //
3731  // pow(x, exp) --> negative if exp is odd and x is negative.
3732  // pow(-0, exp) --> -inf if exp is negative odd.
3733  // pow(-0, exp) --> -0 if exp is positive odd.
3734  // pow(-inf, exp) --> -0 if exp is negative odd.
3735  // pow(-inf, exp) --> -inf if exp is positive odd.
3736  //
3737  // Therefore, if !SignBitOnly, we can return true if x >= +0 or x is NaN,
3738  // but we must return false if x == -0. Unfortunately we do not currently
3739  // have a way of expressing this constraint. See details in
3740  // https://llvm.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=31702.
3741  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3742  Depth + 1);
3743 
3744  case Intrinsic::fma:
3745  case Intrinsic::fmuladd:
3746  // x*x+y is non-negative if y is non-negative.
3747  return I->getOperand(0) == I->getOperand(1) &&
3748  (!SignBitOnly || cast<FPMathOperator>(I)->hasNoNaNs()) &&
3749  cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(2), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3750  Depth + 1);
3751  }
3752  break;
3753  }
3754  return false;
3755 }
3756 
3757 bool llvm::CannotBeOrderedLessThanZero(const Value *V,
3758  const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
3759  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(V, TLI, false, 0);
3760 }
3761 
3762 bool llvm::SignBitMustBeZero(const Value *V, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
3763  return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(V, TLI, true, 0);
3764 }
3765 
3766 bool llvm::isKnownNeverInfinity(const Value *V, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI,
3767  unsigned Depth) {
3768  assert(V->getType()->isFPOrFPVectorTy() && "Querying for Inf on non-FP type");
3769 
3770  // If we're told that infinities won't happen, assume they won't.
3771  if (auto *FPMathOp = dyn_cast<FPMathOperator>(V))
3772  if (FPMathOp->hasNoInfs())
3773  return true;
3774 
3775  // Handle scalar constants.
3776  if (auto *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(V))
3777  return !CFP->isInfinity();
3778 
3779  if (Depth == MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
3780  return false;
3781 
3782  if (auto *Inst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {
3783  switch (Inst->getOpcode()) {
3784  case Instruction::Select: {
3785  return isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3786  isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(2), TLI, Depth + 1);
3787  }
3788  case Instruction::SIToFP:
3789  case Instruction::UIToFP: {
3790  // Get width of largest magnitude integer (remove a bit if signed).
3791  // This still works for a signed minimum value because the largest FP
3792  // value is scaled by some fraction close to 2.0 (1.0 + 0.xxxx).
3793  int IntSize = Inst->getOperand(0)->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
3794  if (Inst->getOpcode() == Instruction::SIToFP)
3795  --IntSize;
3796 
3797  // If the exponent of the largest finite FP value can hold the largest
3798  // integer, the result of the cast must be finite.
3799  Type *FPTy = Inst->getType()->getScalarType();
3800  return ilogb(APFloat::getLargest(FPTy->getFltSemantics())) >= IntSize;
3801  }
3802  case Instruction::FNeg:
3803  case Instruction::FPExt: {
3804  // Peek through to source op. If it is not infinity, this is not infinity.
3805  return isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3806  }
3807  case Instruction::FPTrunc: {
3808  // Need a range check.
3809  return false;
3810  }
3811  default:
3812  break;
3813  }
3814 
3815  if (const auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(V)) {
3816  switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
3817  case Intrinsic::sin:
3818  case Intrinsic::cos:
3819  // Return NaN on infinite inputs.
3820  return true;
3821  case Intrinsic::fabs:
3822  case Intrinsic::sqrt:
3823  case Intrinsic::canonicalize:
3824  case Intrinsic::copysign:
3825  case Intrinsic::arithmetic_fence:
3826  case Intrinsic::trunc:
3827  return isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3828  case Intrinsic::floor:
3829  case Intrinsic::ceil:
3830  case Intrinsic::rint:
3831  case Intrinsic::nearbyint:
3832  case Intrinsic::round:
3833  case Intrinsic::roundeven:
3834  // PPC_FP128 is a special case.
3835  if (V->getType()->isMultiUnitFPType())
3836  return false;
3837  return isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3838  case Intrinsic::fptrunc_round:
3839  // Requires knowing the value range.
3840  return false;
3841  case Intrinsic::minnum:
3842  case Intrinsic::maxnum:
3843  case Intrinsic::minimum:
3844  case Intrinsic::maximum:
3845  return isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3846  isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1);
3847  case Intrinsic::log:
3848  case Intrinsic::log10:
3849  case Intrinsic::log2:
3850  // log(+inf) -> +inf
3851  // log([+-]0.0) -> -inf
3852  // log(-inf) -> nan
3853  // log(-x) -> nan
3854  // TODO: We lack API to check the == 0 case.
3855  return false;
3856  case Intrinsic::exp:
3857  case Intrinsic::exp2:
3858  case Intrinsic::pow:
3859  case Intrinsic::powi:
3860  case Intrinsic::fma:
3861  case Intrinsic::fmuladd:
3862  // These can return infinities on overflow cases, so it's hard to prove
3863  // anything about it.
3864  return false;
3865  default:
3866  break;
3867  }
3868  }
3869  }
3870 
3871  // try to handle fixed width vector constants
3872  auto *VFVTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(V->getType());
3873  if (VFVTy && isa<Constant>(V)) {
3874  // For vectors, verify that each element is not infinity.
3875  unsigned NumElts = VFVTy->getNumElements();
3876  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
3877  Constant *Elt = cast<Constant>(V)->getAggregateElement(i);
3878  if (!Elt)
3879  return false;
3880  if (isa<UndefValue>(Elt))
3881  continue;
3882  auto *CElt = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(Elt);
3883  if (!CElt || CElt->isInfinity())
3884  return false;
3885  }
3886  // All elements were confirmed non-infinity or undefined.
3887  return true;
3888  }
3889 
3890  // was not able to prove that V never contains infinity
3891  return false;
3892 }
3893 
3894 bool llvm::isKnownNeverNaN(const Value *V, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI,
3895  unsigned Depth) {
3896  assert(V->getType()->isFPOrFPVectorTy() && "Querying for NaN on non-FP type");
3897 
3898  // If we're told that NaNs won't happen, assume they won't.
3899  if (auto *FPMathOp = dyn_cast<FPMathOperator>(V))
3900  if (FPMathOp->hasNoNaNs())
3901  return true;
3902 
3903  // Handle scalar constants.
3904  if (auto *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(V))
3905  return !CFP->isNaN();
3906 
3907  if (Depth == MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
3908  return false;
3909 
3910  if (auto *Inst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {
3911  switch (Inst->getOpcode()) {
3912  case Instruction::FAdd:
3913  case Instruction::FSub:
3914  // Adding positive and negative infinity produces NaN.
3915  return isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3916  isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3917  (isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) ||
3918  isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1));
3919 
3920  case Instruction::FMul:
3921  // Zero multiplied with infinity produces NaN.
3922  // FIXME: If neither side can be zero fmul never produces NaN.
3923  return isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3924  isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3925  isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3926  isKnownNeverInfinity(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1);
3927 
3928  case Instruction::FDiv:
3929  case Instruction::FRem:
3930  // FIXME: Only 0/0, Inf/Inf, Inf REM x and x REM 0 produce NaN.
3931  return false;
3932 
3933  case Instruction::Select: {
3934  return isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3935  isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(2), TLI, Depth + 1);
3936  }
3937  case Instruction::SIToFP:
3938  case Instruction::UIToFP:
3939  return true;
3940  case Instruction::FPTrunc:
3941  case Instruction::FPExt:
3942  case Instruction::FNeg:
3943  return isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3944  default:
3945  break;
3946  }
3947  }
3948 
3949  if (const auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(V)) {
3950  switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
3951  case Intrinsic::canonicalize:
3952  case Intrinsic::fabs:
3953  case Intrinsic::copysign:
3954  case Intrinsic::exp:
3955  case Intrinsic::exp2:
3956  case Intrinsic::floor:
3957  case Intrinsic::ceil:
3958  case Intrinsic::trunc:
3959  case Intrinsic::rint:
3960  case Intrinsic::nearbyint:
3961  case Intrinsic::round:
3962  case Intrinsic::roundeven:
3963  case Intrinsic::arithmetic_fence:
3964  return isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3965  case Intrinsic::sqrt:
3966  return isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3967  CannotBeOrderedLessThanZero(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI);
3968  case Intrinsic::minnum:
3969  case Intrinsic::maxnum:
3970  // If either operand is not NaN, the result is not NaN.
3971  return isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) ||
3972  isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1);
3973  default:
3974  return false;
3975  }
3976  }
3977 
3978  // Try to handle fixed width vector constants
3979  auto *VFVTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(V->getType());
3980  if (VFVTy && isa<Constant>(V)) {
3981  // For vectors, verify that each element is not NaN.
3982  unsigned NumElts = VFVTy->getNumElements();
3983  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
3984  Constant *Elt = cast<Constant>(V)->getAggregateElement(i);
3985  if (!Elt)
3986  return false;
3987  if (isa<UndefValue>(Elt))
3988  continue;
3989  auto *CElt = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(Elt);
3990  if (!CElt || CElt->isNaN())
3991  return false;
3992  }
3993  // All elements were confirmed not-NaN or undefined.
3994  return true;
3995  }
3996 
3997  // Was not able to prove that V never contains NaN
3998  return false;
3999 }
4000 
4001 Value *llvm::isBytewiseValue(Value *V, const DataLayout &DL) {
4002 
4003  // All byte-wide stores are splatable, even of arbitrary variables.
4004  if (V->getType()->isIntegerTy(8))
4005  return V;
4006 
4007  LLVMContext &Ctx = V->getContext();
4008 
4009  // Undef don't care.
4010  auto *UndefInt8 = UndefValue::get(Type::getInt8Ty(Ctx));
4011  if (isa<UndefValue>(V))
4012  return UndefInt8;
4013 
4014  // Return Undef for zero-sized type.
4015  if (!DL.getTypeStoreSize(V->getType()).isNonZero())
4016  return UndefInt8;
4017 
4018  Constant *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(V);
4019  if (!C) {
4020  // Conceptually, we could handle things like:
4021  // %a = zext i8 %X to i16
4022  // %b = shl i16 %a, 8
4023  // %c = or i16 %a, %b
4024  // but until there is an example that actually needs this, it doesn't seem
4025  // worth worrying about.
4026  return nullptr;
4027  }
4028 
4029  // Handle 'null' ConstantArrayZero etc.
4030  if (C->isNullValue())
4031  return Constant::getNullValue(Type::getInt8Ty(Ctx));
4032 
4033  // Constant floating-point values can be handled as integer values if the
4034  // corresponding integer value is "byteable". An important case is 0.0.
4035  if (ConstantFP *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(C)) {
4036  Type *Ty = nullptr;
4037  if (CFP->getType()->isHalfTy())
4038  Ty = Type::getInt16Ty(Ctx);
4039  else if (CFP->getType()->isFloatTy())
4040  Ty = Type::getInt32Ty(Ctx);
4041  else if (CFP->getType()->isDoubleTy())
4042  Ty = Type::getInt64Ty(Ctx);
4043  // Don't handle long double formats, which have strange constraints.
4044  return Ty ? isBytewiseValue(ConstantExpr::getBitCast(CFP, Ty), DL)
4045  : nullptr;
4046  }
4047 
4048  // We can handle constant integers that are multiple of 8 bits.
4049  if (ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(C)) {
4050  if (CI->getBitWidth() % 8 == 0) {
4051  assert(CI->getBitWidth() > 8 && "8 bits should be handled above!");
4052  if (!CI->getValue().isSplat(8))
4053  return nullptr;
4054  return ConstantInt::get(Ctx, CI->getValue().trunc(8));
4055  }
4056  }
4057 
4058  if (auto *CE = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(C)) {
4059  if (CE->getOpcode() == Instruction::IntToPtr) {
4060  if (auto *PtrTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(CE->getType())) {
4061  unsigned BitWidth = DL.getPointerSizeInBits(PtrTy->getAddressSpace());
4062  return isBytewiseValue(
4063  ConstantExpr::getIntegerCast(CE->getOperand(0),
4064  Type::getIntNTy(Ctx, BitWidth), false),
4065  DL);
4066  }
4067  }
4068  }
4069 
4070  auto Merge = [&](Value *LHS, Value *RHS) -> Value * {
4071  if (LHS == RHS)
4072  return LHS;
4073  if (!LHS || !RHS)
4074  return nullptr;
4075  if (LHS == UndefInt8)
4076  return RHS;
4077  if (RHS == UndefInt8)
4078  return LHS;
4079  return nullptr;
4080  };
4081 
4082  if (ConstantDataSequential *CA = dyn_cast<ConstantDataSequential>(C)) {
4083  Value *Val = UndefInt8;
4084  for (unsigned I = 0, E = CA->getNumElements(); I != E; ++I)
4085  if (!(Val = Merge(Val, isBytewiseValue(CA->getElementAsConstant(I), DL))))
4086  return nullptr;
4087  return Val;
4088  }
4089 
4090  if (isa<ConstantAggregate>(C)) {
4091  Value *Val = UndefInt8;
4092  for (unsigned I = 0, E = C->getNumOperands(); I != E; ++I)
4093  if (!(Val = Merge(Val, isBytewiseValue(C->getOperand(I), DL))))
4094  return nullptr;
4095  return Val;
4096  }
4097 
4098  // Don't try to handle the handful of other constants.
4099  return nullptr;
4100 }
4101 
4102 // This is the recursive version of BuildSubAggregate. It takes a few different
4103 // arguments. Idxs is the index within the nested struct From that we are
4104 // looking at now (which is of type IndexedType). IdxSkip is the number of
4105 // indices from Idxs that should be left out when inserting into the resulting
4106 // struct. To is the result struct built so far, new insertvalue instructions
4107 // build on that.
4108 static Value *BuildSubAggregate(Value *From, Value* To, Type *IndexedType,
4109  SmallVectorImpl<unsigned> &Idxs,
4110  unsigned IdxSkip,
4111  Instruction *InsertBefore) {
4112  StructType *STy = dyn_cast<StructType>(IndexedType);
4113  if (STy) {
4114  // Save the original To argument so we can modify it
4115  Value *OrigTo = To;
4116  // General case, the type indexed by Idxs is a struct
4117  for (unsigned i = 0, e = STy->getNumElements(); i != e; ++i) {
4118  // Process each struct element recursively
4119  Idxs.push_back(i);
4120  Value *PrevTo = To;
4121  To = BuildSubAggregate(From, To, STy->getElementType(i), Idxs, IdxSkip,
4122  InsertBefore);
4123  Idxs.pop_back();
4124  if (!To) {
4125  // Couldn't find any inserted value for this index? Cleanup
4126  while (PrevTo != OrigTo) {
4127  InsertValueInst* Del = cast<InsertValueInst>(PrevTo);
4128  PrevTo = Del->getAggregateOperand();
4129  Del->eraseFromParent();
4130  }
4131  // Stop processing elements
4132  break;
4133  }
4134  }
4135  // If we successfully found a value for each of our subaggregates
4136  if (To)
4137  return To;
4138  }
4139  // Base case, the type indexed by SourceIdxs is not a struct, or not all of
4140  // the struct's elements had a value that was inserted directly. In the latter
4141  // case, perhaps we can't determine each of the subelements individually, but
4142  // we might be able to find the complete struct somewhere.
4143 
4144  // Find the value that is at that particular spot
4145  Value *V = FindInsertedValue(From, Idxs);
4146 
4147  if (!V)
4148  return nullptr;
4149 
4150  // Insert the value in the new (sub) aggregate
4151  return InsertValueInst::Create(To, V, ArrayRef(Idxs).slice(IdxSkip), "tmp",
4152  InsertBefore);
4153 }
4154 
4155 // This helper takes a nested struct and extracts a part of it (which is again a
4156 // struct) into a new value. For example, given the struct:
4157 // { a, { b, { c, d }, e } }
4158 // and the indices "1, 1" this returns
4159 // { c, d }.
4160 //
4161 // It does this by inserting an insertvalue for each element in the resulting
4162 // struct, as opposed to just inserting a single struct. This will only work if
4163 // each of the elements of the substruct are known (ie, inserted into From by an
4164 // insertvalue instruction somewhere).
4165 //
4166 // All inserted insertvalue instructions are inserted before InsertBefore
4167 static Value *BuildSubAggregate(Value *From, ArrayRef<unsigned> idx_range,
4168  Instruction *InsertBefore) {
4169  assert(InsertBefore && "Must have someplace to insert!");
4170  Type *IndexedType = ExtractValueInst::getIndexedType(From->getType(),
4171  idx_range);
4172  Value *To = PoisonValue::get(IndexedType);
4173  SmallVector<unsigned, 10> Idxs(idx_range.begin(), idx_range.end());
4174  unsigned IdxSkip = Idxs.size();
4175 
4176  return BuildSubAggregate(From, To, IndexedType, Idxs, IdxSkip, InsertBefore);
4177 }
4178 
4179 /// Given an aggregate and a sequence of indices, see if the scalar value
4180 /// indexed is already around as a register, for example if it was inserted
4181 /// directly into the aggregate.
4182 ///
4183 /// If InsertBefore is not null, this function will duplicate (modified)
4184 /// insertvalues when a part of a nested struct is extracted.
4185 Value *llvm::FindInsertedValue(Value *V, ArrayRef<unsigned> idx_range,
4186  Instruction *InsertBefore) {
4187  // Nothing to index? Just return V then (this is useful at the end of our
4188  // recursion).
4189  if (idx_range.empty())
4190  return V;
4191  // We have indices, so V should have an indexable type.
4192  assert((V->getType()->isStructTy() || V->getType()->isArrayTy()) &&
4193  "Not looking at a struct or array?");
4194  assert(ExtractValueInst::getIndexedType(V->getType(), idx_range) &&
4195  "Invalid indices for type?");
4196 
4197  if (Constant *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(V)) {
4198  C = C->getAggregateElement(idx_range[0]);
4199  if (!C) return nullptr;
4200  return FindInsertedValue(C, idx_range.slice(1), InsertBefore);
4201  }
4202 
4203  if (InsertValueInst *I = dyn_cast<InsertValueInst>(V)) {
4204  // Loop the indices for the insertvalue instruction in parallel with the
4205  // requested indices
4206  const unsigned *req_idx = idx_range.begin();
4207  for (const unsigned *i = I->idx_begin(), *e = I->idx_end();
4208  i != e; ++i, ++req_idx) {
4209  if (req_idx == idx_range.end()) {
4210  // We can't handle this without inserting insertvalues
4211  if (!InsertBefore)
4212  return nullptr;
4213 
4214  // The requested index identifies a part of a nested aggregate. Handle
4215  // this specially. For example,
4216  // %A = insertvalue { i32, {i32, i32 } } undef, i32 10, 1, 0
4217  // %B = insertvalue { i32, {i32, i32 } } %A, i32 11, 1, 1
4218  // %C = extractvalue {i32, { i32, i32 } } %B, 1
4219  // This can be changed into
4220  // %A = insertvalue {i32, i32 } undef, i32 10, 0
4221  // %C = insertvalue {i32, i32 } %A, i32 11, 1
4222  // which allows the unused 0,0 element from the nested struct to be
4223  // removed.
4224  return BuildSubAggregate(V, ArrayRef(idx_range.begin(), req_idx),
4225  InsertBefore);
4226  }
4227 
4228  // This insert value inserts something else than what we are looking for.
4229  // See if the (aggregate) value inserted into has the value we are
4230  // looking for, then.
4231  if (*req_idx != *i)
4232  return FindInsertedValue(I->getAggregateOperand(), idx_range,
4233  InsertBefore);
4234  }
4235  // If we end up here, the indices of the insertvalue match with those
4236  // requested (though possibly only partially). Now we recursively look at
4237  // the inserted value, passing any remaining indices.
4238  return FindInsertedValue(I->getInsertedValueOperand(),
4239  ArrayRef(req_idx, idx_range.end()), InsertBefore);
4240  }
4241 
4242  if (ExtractValueInst *I = dyn_cast<ExtractValueInst>(V)) {
4243  // If we're extracting a value from an aggregate that was extracted from
4244  // something else, we can extract from that something else directly instead.
4245  // However, we will need to chain I's indices with the requested indices.
4246 
4247  // Calculate the number of indices required
4248  unsigned size = I->getNumIndices() + idx_range.size();
4249  // Allocate some space to put the new indices in
4250  SmallVector<unsigned, 5> Idxs;
4251  Idxs.reserve(size);
4252  // Add indices from the extract value instruction
4253  Idxs.append(I->idx_begin(), I->idx_end());
4254 
4255  // Add requested indices
4256  Idxs.append(idx_range.begin(), idx_range.end());
4257 
4258  assert(Idxs.size() == size
4259  && "Number of indices added not correct?");
4260 
4261  return FindInsertedValue(I->getAggregateOperand(), Idxs, InsertBefore);
4262  }
4263  // Otherwise, we don't know (such as, extracting from a function return value
4264  // or load instruction)
4265  return nullptr;
4266 }
4267 
4268 bool llvm::isGEPBasedOnPointerToString(const GEPOperator *GEP,
4269  unsigned CharSize) {
4270  // Make sure the GEP has exactly three arguments.
4271  if (GEP->getNumOperands() != 3)
4272  return false;
4273 
4274  // Make sure the index-ee is a pointer to array of \p CharSize integers.
4275  // CharSize.
4276  ArrayType *AT = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(GEP->getSourceElementType());
4277  if (!AT || !AT->getElementType()->isIntegerTy(CharSize))
4278  return false;
4279 
4280  // Check to make sure that the first operand of the GEP is an integer and
4281  // has value 0 so that we are sure we're indexing into the initializer.
4282  const ConstantInt *FirstIdx = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(GEP->getOperand(1));
4283  if (!FirstIdx || !FirstIdx->isZero())
4284  return false;
4285 
4286  return true;
4287 }
4288 
4289 // If V refers to an initialized global constant, set Slice either to
4290 // its initializer if the size of its elements equals ElementSize, or,
4291 // for ElementSize == 8, to its representation as an array of unsiged
4292 // char. Return true on success.
4293 // Offset is in the unit "nr of ElementSize sized elements".
4294 bool llvm::getConstantDataArrayInfo(const Value *V,
4295  ConstantDataArraySlice &Slice,
4296  unsigned ElementSize, uint64_t Offset) {
4297  assert(V && "V should not be null.");
4298  assert((ElementSize % 8) == 0 &&
4299  "ElementSize expected to be a multiple of the size of a byte.");
4300  unsigned ElementSizeInBytes = ElementSize / 8;
4301 
4302  // Drill down into the pointer expression V, ignoring any intervening
4303  // casts, and determine the identity of the object it references along
4304  // with the cumulative byte offset into it.
4305  const GlobalVariable *GV =
4306  dyn_cast<GlobalVariable>(getUnderlyingObject(V));
4307  if (!GV || !GV->isConstant() || !GV->hasDefinitiveInitializer())
4308  // Fail if V is not based on constant global object.
4309  return false;
4310 
4311  const DataLayout &DL = GV->getParent()->getDataLayout();
4312  APInt Off(DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(V->getType()), 0);
4313
