4314  if (GV != V->stripAndAccumulateConstantOffsets(DL, Off,
4315  /*AllowNonInbounds*/ true))
4316  // Fail if a constant offset could not be determined.
4317  return false;
4318 
4319  uint64_t StartIdx = Off.getLimitedValue();
4320  if (StartIdx == UINT64_MAX)
4321  // Fail if the constant offset is excessive.
4322  return false;
4323 
4324  // Off/StartIdx is in the unit of bytes. So we need to convert to number of
4325  // elements. Simply bail out if that isn't possible.
4326  if ((StartIdx % ElementSizeInBytes) != 0)
4327  return false;
4328 
4329  Offset += StartIdx / ElementSizeInBytes;
4330  ConstantDataArray *Array = nullptr;
4331  ArrayType *ArrayTy = nullptr;
4332 
4333  if (GV->getInitializer()->isNullValue()) {
4334  Type *GVTy = GV->getValueType();
4335  uint64_t SizeInBytes = DL.getTypeStoreSize(GVTy).getFixedValue();
4336  uint64_t Length = SizeInBytes / ElementSizeInBytes;
4337 
4338  Slice.Array = nullptr;
4339  Slice.Offset = 0;
4340  // Return an empty Slice for undersized constants to let callers
4341  // transform even undefined library calls into simpler, well-defined
4342  // expressions. This is preferable to making the calls although it
4343  // prevents sanitizers from detecting such calls.
4344  Slice.Length = Length < Offset ? 0 : Length - Offset;
4345  return true;
4346  }
4347 
4348  auto *Init = const_cast<Constant *>(GV->getInitializer());
4349  if (auto *ArrayInit = dyn_cast<ConstantDataArray>(Init)) {
4350  Type *InitElTy = ArrayInit->getElementType();
4351  if (InitElTy->isIntegerTy(ElementSize)) {
4352  // If Init is an initializer for an array of the expected type
4353  // and size, use it as is.
4354  Array = ArrayInit;
4355  ArrayTy = ArrayInit->getType();
4356  }
4357  }
4358 
4359  if (!Array) {
4360  if (ElementSize != 8)
4361  // TODO: Handle conversions to larger integral types.
4362  return false;
4363 
4364  // Otherwise extract the portion of the initializer starting
4365  // at Offset as an array of bytes, and reset Offset.
4366  Init = ReadByteArrayFromGlobal(GV, Offset);
4367  if (!Init)
4368  return false;
4369 
4370  Offset = 0;
4371  Array = dyn_cast<ConstantDataArray>(Init);
4372  ArrayTy = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(Init->getType());
4373  }
4374 
4375  uint64_t NumElts = ArrayTy->getArrayNumElements();
4376  if (Offset > NumElts)
4377  return false;
4378 
4379  Slice.Array = Array;
4380  Slice.Offset = Offset;
4381  Slice.Length = NumElts - Offset;
4382  return true;
4383 }
4384 
4385 /// Extract bytes from the initializer of the constant array V, which need
4386 /// not be a nul-terminated string. On success, store the bytes in Str and
4387 /// return true. When TrimAtNul is set, Str will contain only the bytes up
4388 /// to but not including the first nul. Return false on failure.
4389 bool llvm::getConstantStringInfo(const Value *V, StringRef &Str,
4390  bool TrimAtNul) {
4391  ConstantDataArraySlice Slice;
4392  if (!getConstantDataArrayInfo(V, Slice, 8))
4393  return false;
4394 
4395  if (Slice.Array == nullptr) {
4396  if (TrimAtNul) {
4397  // Return a nul-terminated string even for an empty Slice. This is
4398  // safe because all existing SimplifyLibcalls callers require string
4399  // arguments and the behavior of the functions they fold is undefined
4400  // otherwise. Folding the calls this way is preferable to making
4401  // the undefined library calls, even though it prevents sanitizers
4402  // from reporting such calls.
4403  Str = StringRef();
4404  return true;
4405  }
4406  if (Slice.Length == 1) {
4407  Str = StringRef("", 1);
4408  return true;
4409  }
4410  // We cannot instantiate a StringRef as we do not have an appropriate string
4411  // of 0s at hand.
4412  return false;
4413  }
4414 
4415  // Start out with the entire array in the StringRef.
4416  Str = Slice.Array->getAsString();
4417  // Skip over 'offset' bytes.
4418  Str = Str.substr(Slice.Offset);
4419 
4420  if (TrimAtNul) {
4421  // Trim off the \0 and anything after it. If the array is not nul
4422  // terminated, we just return the whole end of string. The client may know
4423  // some other way that the string is length-bound.
4424  Str = Str.substr(0, Str.find('\0'));
4425  }
4426  return true;
4427 }
4428 
4429 // These next two are very similar to the above, but also look through PHI
4430 // nodes.
4431 // TODO: See if we can integrate these two together.
4432 
4433 /// If we can compute the length of the string pointed to by
4434 /// the specified pointer, return 'len+1'. If we can't, return 0.
4435 static uint64_t GetStringLengthH(const Value *V,
4436  SmallPtrSetImpl<const PHINode*> &PHIs,
4437  unsigned CharSize) {
4438  // Look through noop bitcast instructions.
4439  V = V->stripPointerCasts();
4440 
4441  // If this is a PHI node, there are two cases: either we have already seen it
4442  // or we haven't.
4443  if (const PHINode *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {
4444  if (!PHIs.insert(PN).second)
4445  return ~0ULL; // already in the set.
4446 
4447  // If it was new, see if all the input strings are the same length.
4448  uint64_t LenSoFar = ~0ULL;
4449  for (Value *IncValue : PN->incoming_values()) {
4450  uint64_t Len = GetStringLengthH(IncValue, PHIs, CharSize);
4451  if (Len == 0) return 0; // Unknown length -> unknown.
4452 
4453  if (Len == ~0ULL) continue;
4454 
4455  if (Len != LenSoFar && LenSoFar != ~0ULL)
4456  return 0; // Disagree -> unknown.
4457  LenSoFar = Len;
4458  }
4459 
4460  // Success, all agree.
4461  return LenSoFar;
4462  }
4463 
4464  // strlen(select(c,x,y)) -> strlen(x) ^ strlen(y)
4465  if (const SelectInst *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V)) {
4466  uint64_t Len1 = GetStringLengthH(SI->getTrueValue(), PHIs, CharSize);
4467  if (Len1 == 0) return 0;
4468  uint64_t Len2 = GetStringLengthH(SI->getFalseValue(), PHIs, CharSize);
4469  if (Len2 == 0) return 0;
4470  if (Len1 == ~0ULL) return Len2;
4471  if (Len2 == ~0ULL) return Len1;
4472  if (Len1 != Len2) return 0;
4473  return Len1;
4474  }
4475 
4476  // Otherwise, see if we can read the string.
4477  ConstantDataArraySlice Slice;
4478  if (!getConstantDataArrayInfo(V, Slice, CharSize))
4479  return 0;
4480 
4481  if (Slice.Array == nullptr)
4482  // Zeroinitializer (including an empty one).
4483  return 1;
4484 
4485  // Search for the first nul character. Return a conservative result even
4486  // when there is no nul. This is safe since otherwise the string function
4487  // being folded such as strlen is undefined, and can be preferable to
4488  // making the undefined library call.
4489  unsigned NullIndex = 0;
4490  for (unsigned E = Slice.Length; NullIndex < E; ++NullIndex) {
4491  if (Slice.Array->getElementAsInteger(Slice.Offset + NullIndex) == 0)
4492  break;
4493  }
4494 
4495  return NullIndex + 1;
4496 }
4497 
4498 /// If we can compute the length of the string pointed to by
4499 /// the specified pointer, return 'len+1'. If we can't, return 0.
4500 uint64_t llvm::GetStringLength(const Value *V, unsigned CharSize) {
4501  if (!V->getType()->isPointerTy())
4502  return 0;
4503 
4504  SmallPtrSet<const PHINode*, 32> PHIs;
4505  uint64_t Len = GetStringLengthH(V, PHIs, CharSize);
4506  // If Len is ~0ULL, we had an infinite phi cycle: this is dead code, so return
4507  // an empty string as a length.
4508  return Len == ~0ULL ? 1 : Len;
4509 }

4511 const Value *
4512 llvm::getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer(const CallBase *Call,
4513  bool MustPreserveNullness) {
4514  assert(Call &&
4515  "getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer only works on nonnull calls");
4516  if (const Value *RV = Call->getReturnedArgOperand())
4517  return RV;
4518  // This can be used only as a aliasing property.
4519  if (isIntrinsicReturningPointerAliasingArgumentWithoutCapturing(
4520  Call, MustPreserveNullness))
4521  return Call->getArgOperand(0);
4522  return nullptr;
4523 }
4524 
4525 bool llvm::isIntrinsicReturningPointerAliasingArgumentWithoutCapturing(
4526  const CallBase *Call, bool MustPreserveNullness) {
4527  switch (Call->getIntrinsicID()) {
4528  case Intrinsic::launder_invariant_group:
4529  case Intrinsic::strip_invariant_group:
4530  case Intrinsic::aarch64_irg:
4531  case Intrinsic::aarch64_tagp:
4532  return true;
4533  case Intrinsic::ptrmask:
4534  return !MustPreserveNullness;
4535  default:
4536  return false;
4537  }
4538 }
4539 
4540 /// \p PN defines a loop-variant pointer to an object. Check if the
4541 /// previous iteration of the loop was referring to the same object as \p PN.
4542 static bool isSameUnderlyingObjectInLoop(const PHINode *PN,
4543  const LoopInfo *LI) {
4544  // Find the loop-defined value.
4545  Loop *L = LI->getLoopFor(PN->getParent());
4546  if (PN->getNumIncomingValues() != 2)
4547  return true;
4548 
4549  // Find the value from previous iteration.
4550  auto *PrevValue = dyn_cast<Instruction>(PN->getIncomingValue(0));
4551  if (!PrevValue || LI->getLoopFor(PrevValue->getParent()) != L)
4552  PrevValue = dyn_cast<Instruction>(PN->getIncomingValue(1));
4553  if (!PrevValue || LI->getLoopFor(PrevValue->getParent()) != L)
4554  return true;
4555 
4556  // If a new pointer is loaded in the loop, the pointer references a different
4557  // object in every iteration. E.g.:
4558  // for (i)
4559  // int *p = a[i];
4560  // ...
4561  if (auto *Load = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(PrevValue))
4562  if (!L->isLoopInvariant(Load->getPointerOperand()))
4563  return false;
4564  return true;
4565 }
4566 
4567 const Value *llvm::getUnderlyingObject(const Value *V, unsigned MaxLookup) {
4568  if (!V->getType()->isPointerTy())
4569  return V;
4570  for (unsigned Count = 0; MaxLookup == 0 || Count < MaxLookup; ++Count) {
4571  if (auto *GEP = dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(V)) {
4572  V = GEP->getPointerOperand();
4573  } else if (Operator::getOpcode(V) == Instruction::BitCast ||
4574  Operator::getOpcode(V) == Instruction::AddrSpaceCast) {
4575  V = cast<Operator>(V)->getOperand(0);
4576  if (!V->getType()->isPointerTy())
4577  return V;
4578  } else if (auto *GA = dyn_cast<GlobalAlias>(V)) {
4579  if (GA->isInterposable())
4580  return V;
4581  V = GA->getAliasee();
4582  } else {
4583  if (auto *PHI = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {
4584  // Look through single-arg phi nodes created by LCSSA.
4585  if (PHI->getNumIncomingValues() == 1) {
4586  V = PHI->getIncomingValue(0);
4587  continue;
4588  }
4589  } else if (auto *Call = dyn_cast<CallBase>(V)) {
4590  // CaptureTracking can know about special capturing properties of some
4591  // intrinsics like launder.invariant.group, that can't be expressed with
4592  // the attributes, but have properties like returning aliasing pointer.
4593  // Because some analysis may assume that nocaptured pointer is not
4594  // returned from some special intrinsic (because function would have to
4595  // be marked with returns attribute), it is crucial to use this function
4596  // because it should be in sync with CaptureTracking. Not using it may
4597  // cause weird miscompilations where 2 aliasing pointers are assumed to
4598  // noalias.
4599  if (auto *RP = getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer(Call, false)) {
4600  V = RP;
4601  continue;
4602  }
4603  }
4604 
4605  return V;
4606  }
4607  assert(V->getType()->isPointerTy() && "Unexpected operand type!");
4608  }
4609  return V;
4610 }
4611 
4612 void llvm::getUnderlyingObjects(const Value *V,
4613  SmallVectorImpl<const Value *> &Objects,
4614  LoopInfo *LI, unsigned MaxLookup) {
4615  SmallPtrSet<const Value *, 4> Visited;
4616  SmallVector<const Value *, 4> Worklist;
4617  Worklist.push_back(V);
4618  do {
4619  const Value *P = Worklist.pop_back_val();
4620  P = getUnderlyingObject(P, MaxLookup);
4621 
4622  if (!Visited.insert(P).second)
4623  continue;
4624 
4625  if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(P)) {
4626  Worklist.push_back(SI->getTrueValue());
4627  Worklist.push_back(SI->getFalseValue());
4628  continue;
4629  }
4630 
4631  if (auto *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(P)) {
4632  // If this PHI changes the underlying object in every iteration of the
4633  // loop, don't look through it. Consider:
4634  // int **A;
4635  // for (i) {
4636  // Prev = Curr; // Prev = PHI (Prev_0, Curr)
4637  // Curr = A[i];
4638  // *Prev, *Curr;
4639  //
4640  // Prev is tracking Curr one iteration behind so they refer to different
4641  // underlying objects.
4642  if (!LI || !LI->isLoopHeader(PN->getParent()) ||
4643  isSameUnderlyingObjectInLoop(PN, LI))
4644  append_range(Worklist, PN->incoming_values());
4645  continue;
4646  }
4647 
4648  Objects.push_back(P);
4649  } while (!Worklist.empty());
4650 }
4651 
4652 /// This is the function that does the work of looking through basic
4653 /// ptrtoint+arithmetic+inttoptr sequences.
4654 static const Value *getUnderlyingObjectFromInt(const Value *V) {
4655  do {
4656  if (const Operator *U = dyn_cast<Operator>(V)) {
4657  // If we find a ptrtoint, we can transfer control back to the
4658  // regular getUnderlyingObjectFromInt.
4659  if (U->getOpcode() == Instruction::PtrToInt)
4660  return U->getOperand(0);
4661  // If we find an add of a constant, a multiplied value, or a phi, it's
4662  // likely that the other operand will lead us to the base
4663  // object. We don't have to worry about the case where the
4664  // object address is somehow being computed by the multiply,
4665  // because our callers only care when the result is an
4666  // identifiable object.
4667  if (U->getOpcode() != Instruction::Add ||
4668  (!isa<ConstantInt>(U->getOperand(1)) &&
4669  Operator::getOpcode(U->getOperand(1)) != Instruction::Mul &&
4670  !isa<PHINode>(U->getOperand(1))))
4671  return V;
4672  V = U->getOperand(0);
4673  } else {
4674  return V;
4675  }
4676  assert(V->getType()->isIntegerTy() && "Unexpected operand type!");
4677  } while (true);
4678 }
4679 
4680 /// This is a wrapper around getUnderlyingObjects and adds support for basic
4681 /// ptrtoint+arithmetic+inttoptr sequences.
4682 /// It returns false if unidentified object is found in getUnderlyingObjects.
4683 bool llvm::getUnderlyingObjectsForCodeGen(const Value *V,
4684  SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &Objects) {
4685  SmallPtrSet<const Value *, 16> Visited;
4686  SmallVector<const Value *, 4> Working(1, V);
4687  do {
4688  V = Working.pop_back_val();
4689 
4690  SmallVector<const Value *, 4> Objs;
4691  getUnderlyingObjects(V, Objs);
4692 
4693  for (const Value *V : Objs) {
4694  if (!Visited.insert(V).second)
4695  continue;
4696  if (Operator::getOpcode(V) == Instruction::IntToPtr) {
4697  const Value *O =
4698  getUnderlyingObjectFromInt(cast<User>(V)->getOperand(0));
4699  if (O->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
4700  Working.push_back(O);
4701  continue;
4702  }
4703  }
4704  // If getUnderlyingObjects fails to find an identifiable object,
4705  // getUnderlyingObjectsForCodeGen also fails for safety.
4706  if (!isIdentifiedObject(V)) {
4707  Objects.clear();
4708  return false;
4709  }
4710  Objects.push_back(const_cast<Value *>(V));
4711  }
4712  } while (!Working.empty());
4713  return true;
4714 }
4715 
4716 AllocaInst *llvm::findAllocaForValue(Value *V, bool OffsetZero) {
4717  AllocaInst *Result = nullptr;
4718  SmallPtrSet<Value *, 4> Visited;
4719  SmallVector<Value *, 4> Worklist;
4720 
4721  auto AddWork = [&](Value *V) {
4722  if (Visited.insert(V).second)
4723  Worklist.push_back(V);
4724  };
4725 
4726  AddWork(V);
4727  do {
4728  V = Worklist.pop_back_val();
4729  assert(Visited.count(V));
4730 
4731  if (AllocaInst *AI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(V)) {
4732  if (Result && Result != AI)
4733  return nullptr;
4734  Result = AI;
4735  } else if (CastInst *CI = dyn_cast<CastInst>(V)) {
4736  AddWork(CI->getOperand(0));
4737  } else if (PHINode *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {
4738  for (Value *IncValue : PN->incoming_values())
4739  AddWork(IncValue);
4740  } else if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V)) {
4741  AddWork(SI->getTrueValue());
4742  AddWork(SI->getFalseValue());
4743  } else if (GetElementPtrInst *GEP = dyn_cast<GetElementPtrInst>(V)) {
4744  if (OffsetZero && !GEP->hasAllZeroIndices())
4745  return nullptr;
4746  AddWork(GEP->getPointerOperand());
4747  } else if (CallBase *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(V)) {
4748  Value *Returned = CB->getReturnedArgOperand();
4749  if (Returned)
4750  AddWork(Returned);
4751  else
4752  return nullptr;
4753  } else {
4754  return nullptr;
4755  }
4756  } while (!Worklist.empty());
4757 
4758  return Result;
4759 }

4761 static bool onlyUsedByLifetimeMarkersOrDroppableInstsHelper(
4762  const Value *V, bool AllowLifetime, bool AllowDroppable) {
4763  for (const User *U : V->users()) {
4764  const IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(U);
4765  if (!II)
4766  return false;
4767 
4768  if (AllowLifetime && II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd())
4769  continue;
4770 
4771  if (AllowDroppable && II->isDroppable())
4772  continue;
4773 
4774  return false;
4775  }
4776  return true;
4777 }
4778 
4779 bool llvm::onlyUsedByLifetimeMarkers(const Value *V) {
4780  return onlyUsedByLifetimeMarkersOrDroppableInstsHelper(
4781  V, /* AllowLifetime */ true, /* AllowDroppable */ false);
4782 }
4783 bool llvm::onlyUsedByLifetimeMarkersOrDroppableInsts(const Value *V) {
4784  return onlyUsedByLifetimeMarkersOrDroppableInstsHelper(
4785  V, /* AllowLifetime */ true, /* AllowDroppable */ true);
4786 }

4788 bool llvm::mustSuppressSpeculation(const LoadInst &LI) {
4789  if (!LI.isUnordered())
4790  return true;
4791  const Function &F = *LI.getFunction();
4792  // Speculative load may create a race that did not exist in the source.
4793  return F.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::SanitizeThread) ||
4794  // Speculative load may load data from dirty regions.
4795  F.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::SanitizeAddress) ||
4796  F.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::SanitizeHWAddress);
4797 }

4799 bool llvm::isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(const Instruction *Inst,
4800  const Instruction *CtxI,
4801  AssumptionCache *AC,
4802  const DominatorTree *DT,
4803  const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
4804  return isSafeToSpeculativelyExecuteWithOpcode(Inst->getOpcode(), Inst, CtxI,
4805  AC, DT, TLI);
4806 }
4807 
4808 bool llvm::isSafeToSpeculativelyExecuteWithOpcode(
4809  unsigned Opcode, const Instruction *Inst, const Instruction *CtxI,
4810  AssumptionCache *AC, const DominatorTree *DT,
4811  const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
4812 #ifndef NDEBUG
4813  if (Inst->getOpcode() != Opcode) {
4814  // Check that the operands are actually compatible with the Opcode override.
4815  auto hasEqualReturnAndLeadingOperandTypes =
4816  [](const Instruction *Inst, unsigned NumLeadingOperands) {
4817  if (Inst->getNumOperands() < NumLeadingOperands)
4818  return false;
4819  const Type *ExpectedType = Inst->getType();
4820  for (unsigned ItOp = 0; ItOp < NumLeadingOperands; ++ItOp)
4821  if (Inst->getOperand(ItOp)->getType() != ExpectedType)
4822  return false;
4823  return true;
4824  };
4825  assert(!Instruction::isBinaryOp(Opcode) ||
4826  hasEqualReturnAndLeadingOperandTypes(Inst, 2));
4827  assert(!Instruction::isUnaryOp(Opcode) ||
4828  hasEqualReturnAndLeadingOperandTypes(Inst, 1));
4829  }
4830 #endif
4831 
4832  switch (Opcode) {
4833  default:
4834  return true;
4835  case Instruction::UDiv:
4836  case Instruction::URem: {
4837  // x / y is undefined if y == 0.
4838  const APInt *V;
4839  if (match(Inst->getOperand(1), m_APInt(V)))
4840  return *V != 0;
4841  return false;
4842  }
4843  case Instruction::SDiv:
4844  case Instruction::SRem: {
4845  // x / y is undefined if y == 0 or x == INT_MIN and y == -1
4846  const APInt *Numerator, *Denominator;
4847  if (!match(Inst->getOperand(1), m_APInt(Denominator)))
4848  return false;
4849  // We cannot hoist this division if the denominator is 0.
4850  if (*Denominator == 0)
4851  return false;
4852  // It's safe to hoist if the denominator is not 0 or -1.
4853  if (!Denominator->isAllOnes())
4854  return true;
4855  // At this point we know that the denominator is -1. It is safe to hoist as
4856  // long we know that the numerator is not INT_MIN.
4857  if (match(Inst->getOperand(0), m_APInt(Numerator)))
4858  return !Numerator->isMinSignedValue();
4859  // The numerator *might* be MinSignedValue.
4860  return false;
4861  }
4862  case Instruction::Load: {
4863  const LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(Inst);
4864  if (!LI)
4865  return false;
4866  if (mustSuppressSpeculation(*LI))
4867  return false;
4868  const DataLayout &DL = LI->getModule()->getDataLayout();
4869  return isDereferenceableAndAlignedPointer(LI->getPointerOperand(),
4870  LI->getType(), LI->getAlign(), DL,
4871  CtxI, AC, DT, TLI);
4872  }
4873  case Instruction::Call: {
4874  auto *CI = dyn_cast<const CallInst>(Inst);
4875  if (!CI)
4876  return false;
4877  const Function *Callee = CI->getCalledFunction();
4878 
4879  // The called function could have undefined behavior or side-effects, even
4880  // if marked readnone nounwind.
4881  return Callee && Callee->isSpeculatable();
4882  }
4883  case Instruction::VAArg:
4884  case Instruction::Alloca:
4885  case Instruction::Invoke:
4886  case Instruction::CallBr:
4887  case Instruction::PHI:
4888  case Instruction::Store:
4889  case Instruction::Ret:
4890  case Instruction::Br:
4891  case Instruction::IndirectBr:
4892  case Instruction::Switch:
4893  case Instruction::Unreachable:
4894  case Instruction::Fence:
4895  case Instruction::AtomicRMW:
4896  case Instruction::AtomicCmpXchg:
4897  case Instruction::LandingPad:
4898  case Instruction::Resume:
4899  case Instruction::CatchSwitch:
4900  case Instruction::CatchPad:
4901  case Instruction::CatchRet:
4902  case Instruction::CleanupPad:
4903  case Instruction::CleanupRet:
4904  return false; // Misc instructions which have effects
4905  }
4906 }
4907 
4908 bool llvm::mayHaveNonDefUseDependency(const Instruction &I) {
4909  if (I.mayReadOrWriteMemory())
4910  // Memory dependency possible
4911  return true;
4912  if (!isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(&I))
4913  // Can't move above a maythrow call or infinite loop. Or if an
4914  // inalloca alloca, above a stacksave call.
4915  return true;
4916  if (!isGuaranteedToTransferExecutionToSuccessor(&I))
4917  // 1) Can't reorder two inf-loop calls, even if readonly
4918  // 2) Also can't reorder an inf-loop call below a instruction which isn't
4919  // safe to speculative execute. (Inverse of above)
4920  return true;
4921  return false;
4922 }

4924 /// Convert ConstantRange OverflowResult into ValueTracking OverflowResult.
4925 static OverflowResult mapOverflowResult(ConstantRange::OverflowResult OR) {
4926  switch (OR) {
4927  case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::MayOverflow:
4928  return OverflowResult::MayOverflow;
4929  case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsLow:
4930  return OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsLow;
4931  case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsHigh:
4932  return OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsHigh;
4933  case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::NeverOverflows:
4934  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
4935  }
4936  llvm_unreachable("Unknown OverflowResult");
4937 }

4939 /// Combine constant ranges from computeConstantRange() and computeKnownBits().
4940 static ConstantRange computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
4941  const Value *V, bool ForSigned, const DataLayout &DL, unsigned Depth,
4942  AssumptionCache *AC, const Instruction *CxtI, const DominatorTree *DT,
4943  OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE = nullptr, bool UseInstrInfo = true) {
4944  KnownBits Known = computeKnownBits(
4945  V, DL, Depth, AC, CxtI, DT, ORE, UseInstrInfo);
4946  ConstantRange CR1 = ConstantRange::fromKnownBits(Known, ForSigned);
4947  ConstantRange CR2 = computeConstantRange(V, UseInstrInfo);
4948  ConstantRange::PreferredRangeType RangeType =
4949  ForSigned ? ConstantRange::Signed : ConstantRange::Unsigned;
4950  return CR1.intersectWith(CR2, RangeType);
4951 }
4952 
4953 OverflowResult llvm::computeOverflowForUnsignedMul(
4954  const Value *LHS, const Value *RHS, const DataLayout &DL,
4955  AssumptionCache *AC, const Instruction *CxtI, const DominatorTree *DT,
4956  bool UseInstrInfo) {
4957  KnownBits LHSKnown = computeKnownBits(LHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
4958  nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
4959  KnownBits RHSKnown = computeKnownBits(RHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
4960  nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
4961  ConstantRange LHSRange = ConstantRange::fromKnownBits(LHSKnown, false);
4962  ConstantRange RHSRange = ConstantRange::fromKnownBits(RHSKnown, false);
4963  return mapOverflowResult(LHSRange.unsignedMulMayOverflow(RHSRange));
4964 }
4965 
4966 OverflowResult
4967 llvm::computeOverflowForSignedMul(const Value *LHS, const Value *RHS,
4968  const DataLayout &DL, AssumptionCache *AC,
4969  const Instruction *CxtI,
4970  const DominatorTree *DT, bool UseInstrInfo) {
4971  // Multiplying n * m significant bits yields a result of n + m significant
4972  // bits. If the total number of significant bits does not exceed the
4973  // result bit width (minus 1), there is no overflow.
4974  // This means if we have enough leading sign bits in the operands
4975  // we can guarantee that the result does not overflow.
4976  // Ref: "Hacker's Delight" by Henry Warren
4977  unsigned BitWidth = LHS->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
4978 
4979  // Note that underestimating the number of sign bits gives a more
4980  // conservative answer.
4981  unsigned SignBits = ComputeNumSignBits(LHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT) +
4982  ComputeNumSignBits(RHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT);
4983 
4984  // First handle the easy case: if we have enough sign bits there's
4985  // definitely no overflow.
4986  if (SignBits > BitWidth + 1)
4987  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
4988 
4989  // There are two ambiguous cases where there can be no overflow:
4990  // SignBits == BitWidth + 1 and
4991  // SignBits == BitWidth
4992  // The second case is difficult to check, therefore we only handle the
4993  // first case.
4994  if (SignBits == BitWidth + 1) {
4995  // It overflows only when both arguments are negative and the true
4996  // product is exactly the minimum negative number.
4997  // E.g. mul i16 with 17 sign bits: 0xff00 * 0xff80 = 0x8000
4998  // For simplicity we just check if at least one side is not negative.
4999  KnownBits LHSKnown = computeKnownBits(LHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
5000  nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
5001  KnownBits RHSKnown = computeKnownBits(RHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
5002  nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
5003  if (LHSKnown.isNonNegative() || RHSKnown.isNonNegative())
5004  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5005  }
5006  return OverflowResult::MayOverflow;
5007 }
5008 
5009 OverflowResult llvm::computeOverflowForUnsignedAdd(
5010  const Value *LHS, const Value *RHS, const DataLayout &DL,
5011  AssumptionCache *AC, const Instruction *CxtI, const DominatorTree *DT,
5012  bool UseInstrInfo) {
5013  ConstantRange LHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5014  LHS, /*ForSigned=*/false, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
5015  nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
5016  ConstantRange RHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5017  RHS, /*ForSigned=*/false, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
5018  nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
5019  return mapOverflowResult(LHSRange.unsignedAddMayOverflow(RHSRange));
5020 }
5021 
5022 static OverflowResult computeOverflowForSignedAdd(const Value *LHS,
5023  const Value *RHS,
5024  const AddOperator *Add,
5025  const DataLayout &DL,
5026  AssumptionCache *AC,
5027  const Instruction *CxtI,
5028  const DominatorTree *DT) {
5029  if (Add && Add->hasNoSignedWrap()) {
5030  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5031  }
5032 
5033  // If LHS and RHS each have at least two sign bits, the addition will look
5034  // like
5035  //
5036  // XX..... +
5037  // YY.....
5038  //
5039  // If the carry into the most significant position is 0, X and Y can't both
5040  // be 1 and therefore the carry out of the addition is also 0.
5041  //
5042  // If the carry into the most significant position is 1, X and Y can't both
5043  // be 0 and therefore the carry out of the addition is also 1.
5044  //
5045  // Since the carry into the most significant position is always equal to
5046  // the carry out of the addition, there is no signed overflow.
5047  if (ComputeNumSignBits(LHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT) > 1 &&
5048  ComputeNumSignBits(RHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT) > 1)
5049  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5050 
5051  ConstantRange LHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5052  LHS, /*ForSigned=*/true, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT);
5053  ConstantRange RHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5054  RHS, /*ForSigned=*/true, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT);
5055  OverflowResult OR =
5056  mapOverflowResult(LHSRange.signedAddMayOverflow(RHSRange));
5057  if (OR != OverflowResult::MayOverflow)
5058  return OR;
5059 
5060  // The remaining code needs Add to be available. Early returns if not so.
5061  if (!Add)
5062  return OverflowResult::MayOverflow;
5063 
5064  // If the sign of Add is the same as at least one of the operands, this add
5065  // CANNOT overflow. If this can be determined from the known bits of the
5066  // operands the above signedAddMayOverflow() check will have already done so.
5067  // The only other way to improve on the known bits is from an assumption, so
5068  // call computeKnownBitsFromAssume() directly.
5069  bool LHSOrRHSKnownNonNegative =
5070  (LHSRange.isAllNonNegative() || RHSRange.isAllNonNegative());
5071  bool LHSOrRHSKnownNegative =
5072  (LHSRange.isAllNegative() || RHSRange.isAllNegative());
5073  if (LHSOrRHSKnownNonNegative || LHSOrRHSKnownNegative) {
5074  KnownBits AddKnown(LHSRange.getBitWidth());
5075  computeKnownBitsFromAssume(
5076  Add, AddKnown, /*Depth=*/0, Query(DL, AC, CxtI, DT, true));
5077  if ((AddKnown.isNonNegative() && LHSOrRHSKnownNonNegative) ||
5078  (AddKnown.isNegative() && LHSOrRHSKnownNegative))
5079  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5080  }
5081 
5082  return OverflowResult::MayOverflow;
5083 }
5084 
5085 OverflowResult llvm::computeOverflowForUnsignedSub(const Value *LHS,
5086  const Value *RHS,
5087  const DataLayout &DL,
5088  AssumptionCache *AC,
5089  const Instruction *CxtI,
5090  const DominatorTree *DT) {
5091  // X - (X % ?)
5092  // The remainder of a value can't have greater magnitude than itself,
5093  // so the subtraction can't overflow.
5094 
5095  // X - (X -nuw ?)
5096  // In the minimal case, this would simplify to "?", so there's no subtract
5097  // at all. But if this analysis is used to peek through casts, for example,
5098  // then determining no-overflow may allow other transforms.
5099 
5100  // TODO: There are other patterns like this.
5101  // See simplifyICmpWithBinOpOnLHS() for candidates.
5102  if (match(RHS, m_URem(m_Specific(LHS), m_Value())) ||
5103  match(RHS, m_NUWSub(m_Specific(LHS), m_Value())))
5104  if (isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(LHS, AC, CxtI, DT))
5105  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5106 
5107  // Checking for conditions implied by dominating conditions may be expensive.
5108  // Limit it to usub_with_overflow calls for now.
5109  if (match(CxtI,
5110  m_Intrinsic<Intrinsic::usub_with_overflow>(m_Value(), m_Value())))
5111  if (auto C =
5112  isImpliedByDomCondition(CmpInst::ICMP_UGE, LHS, RHS, CxtI, DL)) {
5113  if (*C)
5114  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5115  return OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsLow;
5116  }
5117  ConstantRange LHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5118  LHS, /*ForSigned=*/false, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT);
5119  ConstantRange RHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5120  RHS, /*ForSigned=*/false, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT);
5121  return mapOverflowResult(LHSRange.unsignedSubMayOverflow(RHSRange));
5122 }
5123 
5124 OverflowResult llvm::computeOverflowForSignedSub(const Value *LHS,
5125  const Value *RHS,
5126  const DataLayout &DL,
5127  AssumptionCache *AC,
5128  const Instruction *CxtI,
5129  const DominatorTree *DT) {
5130  // X - (X % ?)
5131  // The remainder of a value can't have greater magnitude than itself,
5132  // so the subtraction can't overflow.
5133 
5134  // X - (X -nsw ?)
5135  // In the minimal case, this would simplify to "?", so there's no subtract
5136  // at all. But if this analysis is used to peek through casts, for example,
5137  // then determining no-overflow may allow other transforms.
5138  if (match(RHS, m_SRem(m_Specific(LHS), m_Value())) ||
5139  match(RHS, m_NSWSub(m_Specific(LHS), m_Value())))
5140  if (isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(LHS, AC, CxtI, DT))
5141  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5142 
5143  // If LHS and RHS each have at least two sign bits, the subtraction
5144  // cannot overflow.
5145  if (ComputeNumSignBits(LHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT) > 1 &&
5146  ComputeNumSignBits(RHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT) > 1)
5147  return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
5148 
5149  ConstantRange LHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5150  LHS, /*ForSigned=*/true, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT);
5151  ConstantRange RHSRange = computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
5152  RHS, /*ForSigned=*/true, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT);
5153  return mapOverflowResult(LHSRange.signedSubMayOverflow(RHSRange));
5154 }
5155 
5156 bool llvm::isOverflowIntrinsicNoWrap(const WithOverflowInst *WO,
5157  const DominatorTree &DT) {
5158  SmallVector<const BranchInst *, 2> GuardingBranches;
5159  SmallVector<const ExtractValueInst *, 2> Results;
5160 
5161  for (const User *U : WO->users()) {
5162  if (const auto *EVI = dyn_cast<ExtractValueInst>(U)) {
5163  assert(EVI->getNumIndices() == 1 && "Obvious from CI's type");
5164 
5165  if (EVI->getIndices()[0] == 0)
5166  Results.push_back(EVI);
5167  else {
5168  assert(EVI->getIndices()[0] == 1 && "Obvious from CI's type");
5169 
5170  for (const auto *U : EVI->users())
5171  if (const auto *B = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(U)) {
5172  assert(B->isConditional() && "How else is it using an i1?");
5173  GuardingBranches.push_back(B);
5174  }
5175  }
5176  } else {
5177  // We are using the aggregate directly in a way we don't want to analyze
5178  // here (storing it to a global, say).
5179  return false;
5180  }
5181  }
5182 
5183  auto AllUsesGuardedByBranch = [&](const BranchInst *BI) {
5184  BasicBlockEdge NoWrapEdge(BI->getParent(), BI->getSuccessor(1));
5185  if (!NoWrapEdge.isSingleEdge())
5186  return false;
5187 
5188  // Check if all users of the add are provably no-wrap.
5189  for (const auto *Result : Results) {
5190  // If the extractvalue itself is not executed on overflow, the we don't
5191  // need to check each use separately, since domination is transitive.
5192  if (DT.dominates(NoWrapEdge, Result->getParent()))
5193  continue;
5194 
5195  for (const auto &RU : Result->uses())
5196  if (!DT.dominates(NoWrapEdge, RU))
5197  return false;
5198  }
5199 
5200  return true;
5201  };
5202 
5203  return llvm::any_of(GuardingBranches, AllUsesGuardedByBranch);
5204 }
5205 
5206 /// Shifts return poison if shiftwidth is larger than the bitwidth.
5207 static bool shiftAmountKnownInRange(const Value *ShiftAmount) {
5208  auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(ShiftAmount);
5209  if (!C)
5210  return false;
5211 
5212  // Shifts return poison if shiftwidth is larger than the bitwidth.
5213  SmallVector<const Constant *, 4> ShiftAmounts;
5214  if (auto *FVTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(C->getType())) {
5215  unsigned NumElts = FVTy->getNumElements();
5216  for (unsigned i = 0; i < NumElts; ++i)
5217  ShiftAmounts.push_back(C->getAggregateElement(i));
5218  } else if (isa<ScalableVectorType>(C->getType()))
5219  return false; // Can't tell, just return false to be safe
5220  else
5221  ShiftAmounts.push_back(C);
5222 
5223  bool Safe = llvm::all_of(ShiftAmounts, [](const Constant *C) {
5224  auto *CI = dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(C);
5225  return CI && CI->getValue().ult(C->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth());
5226  });
5227 
5228  return Safe;
5229 }
5230 
5231 static bool canCreateUndefOrPoison(const Operator *Op, bool PoisonOnly,
5232  bool ConsiderFlagsAndMetadata) {
5233 
5234  if (ConsiderFlagsAndMetadata && Op->hasPoisonGeneratingFlagsOrMetadata())
5235  return true;
5236 
5237  unsigned Opcode = Op->getOpcode();
5238 
5239  // Check whether opcode is a poison/undef-generating operation
5240  switch (Opcode) {
5241  case Instruction::Shl:
5242  case Instruction::AShr:
5243  case Instruction::LShr:
5244  return !shiftAmountKnownInRange(Op->getOperand(1));
5245  case Instruction::FPToSI:
5246  case Instruction::FPToUI:
5247  // fptosi/ui yields poison if the resulting value does not fit in the
5248  // destination type.
5249  return true;
5250  case Instruction::Call:
5251  if (auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(Op)) {
5252  switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
5253  // TODO: Add more intrinsics.
5254  case Intrinsic::ctlz:
5255  case Intrinsic::cttz:
5256  case Intrinsic::abs:
5257  if (cast<ConstantInt>(II->getArgOperand(1))->isNullValue())
5258  return false;
5259  break;
5260  case Intrinsic::ctpop:
5261  case Intrinsic::bswap:
5262  case Intrinsic::bitreverse:
5263  case Intrinsic::fshl:
5264  case Intrinsic::fshr:
5265  case Intrinsic::smax:
5266  case Intrinsic::smin:
5267  case Intrinsic::umax:
5268  case Intrinsic::umin:
5269  case Intrinsic::ptrmask:
5270  case Intrinsic::fptoui_sat:
5271  case Intrinsic::fptosi_sat:
5272  case Intrinsic::sadd_with_overflow:
5273  case Intrinsic::ssub_with_overflow:
5274  case Intrinsic::smul_with_overflow:
5275  case Intrinsic::uadd_with_overflow:
5276  case Intrinsic::usub_with_overflow:
5277  case Intrinsic::umul_with_overflow:
5278  case Intrinsic::sadd_sat:
5279  case Intrinsic::uadd_sat:
5280  case Intrinsic::ssub_sat:
5281  case Intrinsic::usub_sat:
5282  return false;
5283  case Intrinsic::sshl_sat:
5284  case Intrinsic::ushl_sat:
5285  return !shiftAmountKnownInRange(II->getArgOperand(1));
5286  case Intrinsic::fma:
5287  case Intrinsic::fmuladd:
5288  case Intrinsic::sqrt:
5289  case Intrinsic::powi:
5290  case Intrinsic::sin:
5291  case Intrinsic::cos:
5292  case Intrinsic::pow:
5293  case Intrinsic::log:
5294  case Intrinsic::log10:
5295  case Intrinsic::log2:
5296  case Intrinsic::exp:
5297  case Intrinsic::exp2:
5298  case Intrinsic::fabs:
5299  case Intrinsic::copysign:
5300  case Intrinsic::floor:
5301  case Intrinsic::ceil:
5302  case Intrinsic::trunc:
5303  case Intrinsic::rint:
5304  case Intrinsic::nearbyint:
5305  case Intrinsic::round:
5306  case Intrinsic::roundeven:
5307  case Intrinsic::fptrunc_round:
5308  case Intrinsic::canonicalize:
5309  case Intrinsic::arithmetic_fence:
5310  case Intrinsic::minnum:
5311  case Intrinsic::maxnum:
5312  case Intrinsic::minimum:
5313  case Intrinsic::maximum:
5314  case Intrinsic::is_fpclass:
5315  return false;
5316  case Intrinsic::lround:
5317  case Intrinsic::llround:
5318  case Intrinsic::lrint:
5319  case Intrinsic::llrint:
5320  // If the value doesn't fit an unspecified value is returned (but this
5321  // is not poison).
5322  return false;
5323  }
5324  }
5325  [[fallthrough]];
5326  case Instruction::CallBr:
5327  case Instruction::Invoke: {
5328  const auto *CB = cast<CallBase>(Op);
5329  return !CB->hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef);
5330  }
5331  case Instruction::InsertElement:
5332  case Instruction::ExtractElement: {
5333  // If index exceeds the length of the vector, it returns poison
5334  auto *VTy = cast<VectorType>(Op->getOperand(0)->getType());
5335  unsigned IdxOp = Op->getOpcode() == Instruction::InsertElement ? 2 : 1;
5336  auto *Idx = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Op->getOperand(IdxOp));
5337  if (!Idx || Idx->getValue().uge(VTy->getElementCount().getKnownMinValue()))
5338  return true;
5339  return false;
5340  }
5341  case Instruction::ShuffleVector: {
5342  // shufflevector may return undef.
5343  if (PoisonOnly)
5344  return false;
5345  ArrayRef<int> Mask = isa<ConstantExpr>(Op)
5346  ? cast<ConstantExpr>(Op)->getShuffleMask()
5347  : cast<ShuffleVectorInst>(Op)->getShuffleMask();
5348  return is_contained(Mask, UndefMaskElem);
5349  }
5350  case Instruction::FNeg:
5351  case Instruction::PHI:
5352  case Instruction::Select:
5353  case Instruction::URem:
5354  case Instruction::SRem:
5355  case Instruction::ExtractValue:
5356  case Instruction::InsertValue:
5357  case Instruction::Freeze:
5358  case Instruction::ICmp:
5359  case Instruction::FCmp:
5360  case Instruction::FAdd:
5361  case Instruction::FSub:
5362  case Instruction::FMul:
5363  case Instruction::FDiv:
5364  case Instruction::FRem:
5365  return false;
5366  case Instruction::GetElementPtr:
5367  // inbounds is handled above
5368  // TODO: what about inrange on constexpr?
5369  return false;
5370  default: {
5371  const auto *CE = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(Op);
5372  if (isa<CastInst>(Op) || (CE && CE->isCast()))
5373  return false;
5374  else if (Instruction::isBinaryOp(Opcode))
5375  return false;
5376  // Be conservative and return true.
5377  return true;
5378  }
5379  }
5380 }

5393 static bool directlyImpliesPoison(const Value *ValAssumedPoison,
5394  const Value *V, unsigned Depth) {
5395  if (ValAssumedPoison == V)
5396  return true;
5397 
5398  const unsigned MaxDepth = 2;
5399  if (Depth >= MaxDepth)
5400  return false;
5401 
5402  if (const auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {
5403  if (any_of(I->operands(), [=](const Use &Op) {
5404  return propagatesPoison(Op) &&
5405  directlyImpliesPoison(ValAssumedPoison, Op, Depth + 1);
5406  }))
5407  return true;
5408 
5409  // V = extractvalue V0, idx
5410  // V2 = extractvalue V0, idx2
5411  // V0's elements are all poison or not. (e.g., add_with_overflow)
5412  const WithOverflowInst *II;
5413  if (match(I, m_ExtractValue(m_WithOverflowInst(II))) &&
5414  (match(ValAssumedPoison, m_ExtractValue(m_Specific(II))) ||
5415  llvm::is_contained(II->args(), ValAssumedPoison)))
5416  return true;
5417  }
5418  return false;
5419 }
5420 
5421 static bool impliesPoison(const Value *ValAssumedPoison, const Value *V,
5422  unsigned Depth) {
5423  if (isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(ValAssumedPoison))
5424  return true;
5425 
5426  if (directlyImpliesPoison(ValAssumedPoison, V, /* Depth */ 0))
5427  return true;
5428 
5429  const unsigned MaxDepth = 2;
5430  if (Depth >= MaxDepth)
5431  return false;
5432 
5433  const auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(ValAssumedPoison);
5434  if (I && !canCreatePoison(cast<Operator>(I))) {
5435  return all_of(I->operands(), [=](const Value *Op) {
5436  return impliesPoison(Op, V, Depth + 1);
5437  });
5438  }
5439  return false;
5440 }

5442 bool llvm::impliesPoison(const Value *ValAssumedPoison, const Value *V) {
5443  return ::impliesPoison(ValAssumedPoison, V, /* Depth */ 0);
5444 }
5445 
5446 static bool programUndefinedIfUndefOrPoison(const Value *V,
5447  bool PoisonOnly);
5448 
5449 static bool isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(const Value *V,
5450  AssumptionCache *AC,
5451  const Instruction *CtxI,
5452  const DominatorTree *DT,
5453  unsigned Depth, bool PoisonOnly) {
5454  if (Depth >= MaxAnalysisRecursionDepth)
5455  return false;
5456 
5457  if (isa<MetadataAsValue>(V))
5458  return false;
5459 
5460  if (const auto *A = dyn_cast<Argument>(V)) {
5461  if (A->hasAttribute(Attribute::NoUndef))
5462  return true;
5463  }
5464 
5465  if (auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(V)) {
5466  if (isa<UndefValue>(C))
5467  return PoisonOnly && !isa<PoisonValue>(C);
5468 
5469  if (isa<ConstantInt>(C) || isa<GlobalVariable>(C) || isa<ConstantFP>(V) ||
5470  isa<ConstantPointerNull>(C) || isa<Function>(C))
5471  return true;
5472 
5473  if (C->getType()->isVectorTy() && !isa<ConstantExpr>(C))
5474  return (PoisonOnly ? !C->containsPoisonElement()
5475  : !C->containsUndefOrPoisonElement()) &&
5476  !C->containsConstantExpression();
5477  }
5478 
5479  // Strip cast operations from a pointer value.
5480  // Note that stripPointerCastsSameRepresentation can strip off getelementptr
5481  // inbounds with zero offset. To guarantee that the result isn't poison, the
5482  // stripped pointer is checked as it has to be pointing into an allocated
5483  // object or be null `null` to ensure `inbounds` getelement pointers with a
5484  // zero offset could not produce poison.
5485  // It can strip off addrspacecast that do not change bit representation as
5486  // well. We believe that such addrspacecast is equivalent to no-op.
5487  auto *StrippedV = V->stripPointerCastsSameRepresentation();
5488  if (isa<AllocaInst>(StrippedV) || isa<GlobalVariable>(StrippedV) ||
5489  isa<Function>(StrippedV) || isa<ConstantPointerNull>(StrippedV))
5490  return true;
5491 
5492  auto OpCheck = [&](const Value *V) {
5493  return isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(V, AC, CtxI, DT, Depth + 1,
5494  PoisonOnly);
5495  };
5496 
5497  if (auto *Opr = dyn_cast<Operator>(V)) {
5498  // If the value is a freeze instruction, then it can never
5499  // be undef or poison.
5500  if (isa<FreezeInst>(V))
5501  return true;
5502 
5503  if (const auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(V)) {
5504  if (CB->hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef))
5505  return true;
5506  }
5507 
5508  if (const auto *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {
5509  unsigned Num = PN->getNumIncomingValues();
5510  bool IsWellDefined = true;
5511  for (unsigned i = 0; i < Num; ++i) {
5512  auto *TI = PN->getIncomingBlock(i)->getTerminator();
5513  if (!isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(PN->getIncomingValue(i), AC, TI,
5514  DT, Depth + 1, PoisonOnly)) {
5515  IsWellDefined = false;
5516  break;
5517  }
5518  }
5519  if (IsWellDefined)
5520  return true;
5521  } else if (!canCreateUndefOrPoison(Opr) && all_of(Opr->operands(), OpCheck))
5522  return true;
5523  }
5524 
5525  if (auto *I = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(V))
5526  if (I->hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_noundef) ||
5527  I->hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_dereferenceable) ||
5528  I->hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_dereferenceable_or_null))
5529  return true;
5530 
5531  if (programUndefinedIfUndefOrPoison(V, PoisonOnly))
5532  return true;
5533 
5534  // CxtI may be null or a cloned instruction.
5535  if (!CtxI || !CtxI->getParent() || !DT)
5536  return false;
5537 
5538  auto *DNode = DT->getNode(CtxI->getParent());
5539  if (!DNode)
5540  // Unreachable block
5541  return false;
5542 
5543  // If V is used as a branch condition before reaching CtxI, V cannot be
5544  // undef or poison.
5545  // br V, BB1, BB2
5546  // BB1:
5547  // CtxI ; V cannot be undef or poison here
5548  auto *Dominator = DNode->getIDom();
5549  while (Dominator) {
5550  auto *TI = Dominator->getBlock()->getTerminator();
5551 
5552  Value *Cond = nullptr;
5553  if (auto BI = dyn_cast_or_null<BranchInst>(TI)) {
5554  if (BI->isConditional())
5555  Cond = BI->getCondition();
5556  } else if (auto SI = dyn_cast_or_null<SwitchInst>(TI)) {
5557  Cond = SI->getCondition();
5558  }
5559 
5560  if (Cond) {
5561  if (Cond == V)
5562  return true;
5563  else if (PoisonOnly && isa<Operator>(Cond)) {
5564  // For poison, we can analyze further
5565  auto *Opr = cast<Operator>(Cond);
5566  if (any_of(Opr->operands(),
5567  [V](const Use &U) { return V == U && propagatesPoison(U); }))
5568  return true;
5569  }
5570  }
5571 
5572  Dominator = Dominator->getIDom();
5573  }
5574 
5575  if (getKnowledgeValidInContext(V, {Attribute::NoUndef}, CtxI, DT, AC))
5576  return true;
5577 
5578  return false;
5579 }
5580 
5581 bool llvm::isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(const Value *V, AssumptionCache *AC,
5582  const Instruction *CtxI,
5583  const DominatorTree *DT,
5584  unsigned Depth) {
5585  return ::isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(V, AC, CtxI, DT, Depth, false);
5586 }
5587 
5588 bool llvm::isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(const Value *V, AssumptionCache *AC,
5589  const Instruction *CtxI,
5590  const DominatorTree *DT, unsigned Depth) {
5591  return ::isGuaranteedNotToBeUndefOrPoison(V, AC, CtxI, DT, Depth, true);
5592 }
